The Higgs boson
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson sparked some attention last summer, and for good reason.
In fact, it is believed that this boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
And finally, this is the last particle whose existence was predicted by the standard model - our best or "least false" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter - but has not yet been observed empirically.
But for the physicists, it is not yet completely certain that it is really the Higgs.
We know without a shadow of a doubt that we have a real new particle, and that it closely resembles the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto, but data is still lacking to be completely certain about it.
Still, let’s assume that it’s actually the Higgs, as there seems to be little risk of deceiving yourself, and let’s look at what it’s all about.
There is an inevitably inevitable law in this world that causes two objects not to be present in the same place at the same time.
It is not possible to break this rule - and don't try too hard as you will hurt yourself.
For even if particle physics is a really strange world, it turns out that there is also such a law for it: the Pauli’s exclusion principle, which says that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time when they are in the same “quantum state”, this “state” consisting largely of some of their properties.
Based on this, physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In a corner are the good citizens who are called Fermione and kindly obey the Pauli principle.
And in the other, the Bosons move, an evil band of anarchists, to whom nothing is sacred - in any case not this principle, which means that they can indeed be in the same place at the same time.
According to the website The Particle Adventure of the Berkeley Laboratories (which is absolutely amazing), these bosons are divided into two groups: the mesons that we will not treat here and the "power particles" through which the great forces of nature spread and with which the Higgs boson would somehow be related.
It must be emphasized here, however, that these bosons are not all as exotic creatures as you might think.
If you are able to read this chronicle, it is only thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon or the "light particle", which is the "message" of electromagnetic force.
In fact, when a particle with an electrical charge accelerates or changes the direction, the electromagnetic field is "interfered" at exactly this location, approximately like a pebble thrown into a pond.
This "disruption" creates an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing more than a photon and thus one of the bosons "carriers of force".
Stable field
The same applies to the Higgs boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs field, needs to be "interfered" in order for this boson to show up.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the pathogen must reach very high energies, somewhat comparable to a frozen pond whose surface could only be shrunk by a very large rock.
That’s why a giant particle accelerator like CERN is required – the Large Hadron Collider is a ring with a circumference of 27 km! – to achieve such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again helpful in explaining the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do this, but others don’t – for example, a sheet of paper would never hold on its own to the fridge.
And likewise, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those who do have a mass, while the others (like the photon by the way) do not have a mass.
What can all this research be "good for," Mrs Plamondon asks?
For science, they are used to verify the standard model (SM), and they also allow physicists to closely study any deviations between the observations and the predictions of the SM.
By the way, there are numerous physicists who yearningly hope that such deviations will be found, since the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and plug some holes in the model.
It has to be said that the latter still has major deficiencies, since it does not offer an explanation for the gravity (ups!) and the dark matter that makes up about 80% of the matter of the universe (up again!).
However, such deviations have not been found at CERN so far.
Effects
The impact of this research on the general population is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there were none.
By the way, in the early 1960s, laser pioneers in Bell laboratories did not suspect that their work would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs where the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who in 1962 developed the first permanent dash laser (the first were pulsed) - has already said that the laser was considered more of a "laboratory playground" in the beginning.
Imagine...
In addition, applications can also result from all the instruments that surround research.
For example, Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor in 1969 during his work in optics.
Although it was not the original purpose, this sensor today serves all digital cameras worldwide as an "eye" and earned it the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities of the LHC will inevitably change our lives, but it does mean that you really can never know...
Palliative care - the best way to die... <0x7C> Le Devoir
Quebec recently discussed the delicate question of the end of life with its committee on "Dignity Dying".
The debate needs to be resumed shortly, although a bill is being prepared.
However, much remains to be done in this important area.
Le Devoir has tried to take a closer look at this.
A few weeks ago Mr. L. lived alone in his apartment in the Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that consumed him had left him a period of two years.
"They gave me five years to live, I've managed seven years," he said half-heartedly, lying in his bed at the Victor-Gadbois palliative care home in Beloeil, where he had arrived the day before.
“However, it’s always a shock, you can’t be prepared for it,” he says.
The disease does its job: an immeasurable weakness prevents him from going to the toilet alone and even eating himself.
Sitting at the table before a delicious lunch, he resigns to be helped with the meal.
Courageously, he even manages to smile and talk to the strangers who are busy around him, bring him his medications, and offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
“My biggest wish is for my diarrhea to be cured because it’s humiliating,” he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this evil.
"Over the course of our lives, we learn that a man is peeing while standing up," says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois home.
Returning to childhood is an unacceptable humiliation for some people.
"It depends on the ability of the person," he notes, to accept a step backwards.
Because according to several people working in palliative care, big events take place in the midst of these setbacks.
The patients who are admitted to the Victor-Gadbois palliative care facility all suffer from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this stage, they are no longer overwhelmed with so-called "healing" care by the doctors and nurses who care for them.
For Ms. A., 89, the worst fear is to die “consciously and by suffocation.”
But through the disease, I really got to know my children.
“I have good children,” she adds.
“I don’t have any wishes in life anymore,” she says before accepting a mask to help her breathe.
She is still expecting a last visit in the next few days from her son, who comes from Italy.
At the Victor-Gadbois home, a group of volunteers offer personal care and help with food intake.
Palliative care is used when there are no other options.
To make dying more enjoyable.
In Quebec, there is a palliative care bed for 11,700 people.
That's very little, considering that we're all going to die one day.
Here life is continued under the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors of the home.
Both at the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
The dying person is given an oral care with brandy or Pepsi as desired.
Diabetics no longer have to check their blood sugar levels.
Death is part of everyday life.
Last night we served Mr. X a beer that died overnight.
This morning his son will drink the beer at the feet of the deceased.
“We are helping family members and patients alike,” said Nathalie Savard, director of nursing.
At the Victor-Gadbois home, no day is like the other.
Alongside a 93-year-old man who enjoys the last family gathering in the courtyard and is well supported by his pillows while being pushed to his honor, a 36-year-old man surrounded by his parents, his wife and his two young children tragically dies after trying everything to survive.
"For six months, three to five beds have always been occupied with cancer patients under the age of 45," Dr. Christiane Martel said.
53% of patients admitted to Victor-Gadbois home come from their homes, 47% from the hospital.
Problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, i.e. care that is intended to alleviate the suffering of patients when the latter have reached the final stage of their lives, both at home, in hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois Home and the Home Palliative Care Society in the Greater Montreal area, specialize more or less exclusively in caring for cancer patients.
It is precisely this great inadequacy in Quebec’s health care that causes several doctors specializing in palliative care to be concerned about passing a law regulating dying and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto has been circulating, signed by prominent palliative care figures such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, to express their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec’s health care system is not powerful enough to ensure that everyone has the right to high-quality palliative care before accepting to go on to death relief.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who was in the ER for 14 days with great pain without taking any steps to relieve her.
I fear that patients want to die only because they do not receive adequate health care.
And at the same time, several oncologists treat their patients, despite the worst predictions, until the last day.
Hélène Richard’s chances of survival were already minimal when she discontinued a cumbersome chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was going to stop treatment, she replied that she regretted that I was giving up the fight, she told me.
She told me that I was at the end!
No omnipotent care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who have asked to die thank the nursing staff for not granting that wish after their pain has been alleviated by a palliative care team.
However, it must be clearly stated that palliative care is not omnipotent in pain treatment.
According to Elsie Monereau, head of palliative care at the Montreal Home Palliative Care Society, 8% of patients do not respond to pain treatment.
At the end of life, doctors often resort to terminal sedation, which results in the patient falling asleep either sporadically or permanently until his death.
We can no longer pretend that we do not perceive this side of suffering.
Patients without pain relief will increasingly have the opportunity to resort to this terminal sedation.
Patients whose pain is not relieved, all say the same sentence: "I want to die."
But that doesn’t necessarily mean, “I want you to put me to sleep,” but “I want my pain to be alleviated.”
