A Constitution with the Breaking Rod in Egypt
This is a new poker game by President Mohammed Mursi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever in terms of the constitutional declaration, which temporarily grants it unlimited power, it has decided to put everything on one map.
To everyone’s surprise, he announced on Wednesday that the constituent assembly would adopt its final version the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of state granted this plenary two additional months to complete its work.
For nearly two years, Egypt has been relying on a provisional text, amended several times, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal confusion.
This new initiative has only led to an even greater division of the country.
For his opponents, the president remains in his “autocratic delirium” by continuing to “break his word” and “trap right.”
His supporters assured that it is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and to speed up the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 14 days.
A very short period of time, forcing the brothers to renounce their intention to explain the text section by section to the Egyptians.
It is also a way for the president to regain his public and democratic legitimacy as the protest rages across the country.
After affirmations in an interview with the American weekly magazine Time, Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote benevolently.
Especially since the Egyptian people are given an ultimatum by resorting to a hasty vote: "Either you vote for my draft or I retain the unlimited power of attorney", the latter should supposedly end after the adoption of the constitution.
85 mostly Islamist members of this constituent assembly passed the text yesterday in a strange atmosphere.
The majority of the Liberals did not comply with the call.
Shortly before the constitutional declaration in mid-November, they turned away because they felt they were unable to showcase their views.
Representatives of human rights organizations, religious minorities or civil society have acted in the same way.
In order to achieve the decision-making capacity, 11 deputy members were added in a hurry yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
It is not surprising that the articles were mostly unanimously adopted.
The commentators found it entertaining, by the way, that the only disagreement of the day... was expressed at the time of prayer, as some members of the board felt that the pendulum clock of the constituent assembly was not accurate.
The text, which was adopted last night, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, which attracted all attention, ultimately remains identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, stating that "the principles of Sharia law are the main source of law".
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is an important demand, had the hope of replacing "the principles" with "the rules", which would have made stricter application possible.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been changed is proof of their good will and their respect for the other members of Egyptian society.
“Psychology” is the reply of the liberals, who see it only as a propaganda strike.
Because according to them, the Islamization of the constitution takes place via other articles.
In particular, they have in mind Article 220, which gives the University of Al-Azhar an advisory function, in particular with regard to verification of conformity with the laws of Sharia law.
According to the Egyptian specialist Sophie Pommier, this is disturbing, since "the people who are asked to comment have not been elected and do not have any democratic legitimacy.
Here you can see the first signs of theocracy.”
The fears of the Liberals are also nurtured by the fact that the next rector of this university is likely to be far less temperate than the current one.
“At the moment there is no concrete religious commitment.
With this constitution we remain within the framework of the bourgeois state.
Most of the lawyers who have worked on this text are not Ulema, but academics who have been trained in part in the French system," says Alexis Blouet, who writes a doctoral thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
However, he admits that “there may be ambiguity in relation to Article 220, since the terms used are borrowed from the religious vocabulary.
One refers here in particular to the "Fiqh" [Islamic jurisprudence, note d. Red.].
And in the future, the question could be raised as to the extent to which civil judges are competent to decide on it.”
In addition to its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is heavily criticized for the far-reaching powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argues that these are significantly reduced compared to the former regime.
Another issue is the powers of the army.
In line with the wishes of the military, the examination of the defence budget is not presented to Parliament, but to a national defence council.
Likewise, there will be no prohibition of civil proceedings in military courts, as the human rights associations have called for.
The latter also share their fears regarding the text they consider to be liberty-threatening.
The act of blasphemy is being maintained, and insults are now prohibited, which could have serious consequences for the right to freedom of expression, especially for the press.
In addition, no longer refers to the protection of women, underlines Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
In her view, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture by Article 36.
This word was not included in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian president had to speak on television last night, demonstrations are planned for this afternoon.
Proponents of the head of state will march on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists await holy sites, the navel of the world and a sea of brine
The Promised Land combines the glory of biblical truths, modern comfort and untouched nature.
AIF gives you the five main reasons to visit Israel.
Prostrate before the holy places
Visit the Jordan River where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that all who bathe in this river receive God’s blessing.
Galilee is the place where Jesus performed his miracles: the transformation of water into wine at a wedding ceremony, walking on the water, the calming of the sea storm and fishing.
Here Jesus appeared to his disciples after the resurrection.
Most of the shrines are found in Jerusalem.
Here believers go on the Path of Suffering or the Way of the Cross of Jesus Christ (in Latin: Via Dolorosa).
The path starts at the Roman fortress Antonia, Pretorium, where the court was, and leads through the streets of the old town to the tomb church on Mount Golgotha, where the crucifixion, an anointing stone and the tomb of Jesus are located.
Here, according to Christian view, is the navel of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of mankind.
The monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem stands at the place where, according to a Christian legend, the tree grew from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus.
Jerusalem is also home to the most holy place of the Jews - the Crying Wall, the remains of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 AD.
Traditionally, people of different faiths leave notebooks with wishes that are then fulfilled.
Take a trip to the heights
The ruins of Masada fortress form the remains of the secret hideout from enemies that Herod the Great built for his family in 25 AD.
They are located on a rock wall in the mountains at 450 meters above sea level.
Only mountaineers can reach the ruins by their own power.
All the others take a cable car to this historic summit.
In the north of the country at an altitude of 1600 to 2040 meters is the famous ski resort Hermon, which attracts countless tourists in the winter months.
From the foot of the mountain you can reach it by shuttle bus.
The ski slopes have a total length of 45 kilometers.
According to an ancient legend, there were supposedly pagan gods living on the top of the mountain.
Visiting unique museums
There are almost 300 museums in this country.
With only one trip, not all of them can be visited.
But at least the five most interesting of them should be visited.
Among them is the Israel Museum near the Knesset (Parliament).
There, ancient Qumra manuscripts or Dead Sea scrolls found in rock caves in the Judean desert are preserved as well as about 500 thousand archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
The Museum of Art in Tel Aviv is also worth a visit.
There, the collection of works by impressionists and expressionists Monet, Pissaro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso will be exhibited.
In Akko you can visit the museum in Bad Al Basha, which houses several rooms of old Turkish baths with sculptures of the visitors and bathers at the time.
In Caesarea you should visit the unique private Ralli Museum, where you can admire sculptures of Dali and Rodin.
There are no museum guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free and donations are generally refused.
The fifth museum, the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, tells of one of the most shocking chapters in history.
The most poignant section is the children’s memorial built to commemorate the 1.5 million children destroyed in concentration camps and gas chambers.
When entering the room there is complete darkness.
Stars sparkle.
And the names of the Jewish children and the countries in which they died are heard.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Doing Something for Health
Israel’s three main recreation areas are located on the shores of the Mediterranean, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
In each of the three places there are swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanariums.
Surprisingly, the Red Sea is also bathed in the winter months, as the water temperature there does not fall below 21 °C and the air warms up to 23 °C.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and bathes there all year round.
By the way, this unusual sea with a location of 417 meters below sea level is the deepest sea in the world.
Its turquoise water has a high salt content, thus carrying even non-swimmers easily on the surface.
The surrounding landscape is indescribably beautiful.
Visitors come here for treatments using salt water (natural salt sole) and healing mud as well as for the treatment of skin inflammation, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes and to calm damaged nerves.
Touching the Secrets of Antiquity
These secrets hold the old town of Tel Aviv, namely the city of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
Through this city, the famous sea route connected Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and ancient Egyptian legends.
According to tradition, Noah built his ark here, and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with which he lived a long and happy life in this place.
Tourists like to stroll through the narrow streets named after zodiac signs.
According to legend, Fortuna is held by anyone who touches the walls in the alleyway with her zodiac sign.
In Jaffa you can meet newlywed couples from all over Israel and even other countries on photo appointments.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can stroll through the Roman theater and conquer the fortress of the Crusaders.
In Roman times Caesarea was the most important city in Judea and residence of Roman governors, including Pontius Pilate.
Nowadays evening concerts and operas are performed in the carefully restored theatre.
A watchlist for tourists
When you travel to Israel, don’t worry about your poor English skills: About 30% of Israelis speak Russian.
The money on the trip is preferable not in euros, but in dollars, which can easily be exchanged in shekels (current exchange rate: 1 dollar to 3.8 shekels).
In the city you can usually travel by bus, but in Jerusalem there is also a highway and in Haifa the only subway line in the country with six stops that connects the lower city to the upper city.
In fact, it is an underground cable car.
A ride within the city costs 6 shekels regardless of the means of transport, which is enough including transfers for a ride of up to 1.5 hours.
According to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated in Israel on Saturdays.
From Friday evening until sunset on Saturday, markets and shops are closed, and public transport rests.
And on Sunday morning, the work week begins.
In many cafes, restaurants and restaurants, only kosher food is served, which excludes pork, seafood, fish without scales and foods that contain both dairy and meat products.
Instead, you can choose from a variety of dishes including beef and beef, soups and desserts (prepared with coconut milk), traditional Jewish humus paste, various sauces, fried balls of pureed beans and peas (falafel) as well as fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs on the streets of Israeli cities.
For this, there are many well-nourished cats that stroll cozy and undisturbed through the streets.
In the evening you can even see them asleep on the rooftops of parked cars.
Cats like busy places and don’t say no to treats.
Depending on the brand, a rental car costs between $37 per day (Hyundai Getz) and $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
The insurance costs an additional $15 per day.
And bicycle rental costs 15 shekels per day.
Tickets for museums cost an average of 30 shekels.
In numbers
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
Most adventurers and recreation seekers came from Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England, USA and Ukraine.
From January to October 2012, 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists entered the Promised Land, an increase of 51% compared to the 2010 comparison period, before the visa requirement was lifted on February 9, 2011.
"The Big and Powerful" Leads to Moscow: Migrants Save Money for Language
While MPs and civil rights activists are discussing the benefits of the law on mandatory language tests for migrants, criminals are already trading with counterfeit certificates
Every year, 13 million workers travel to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other cities in Russia.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money for the maintenance of the families left in the home.
On December 1, a law came into force that requires every labor migrant to take a test that certifies knowledge of the Russian language.
Until now, this scheme only applies to migrants who want to work in the service sector, in the municipal housing industry and in the retail sector.
However, over time, the tests will become mandatory for all guest workers, according to the Federal Migration Authority.
You have to take not only language tests, but also tests in Russian history and the basics of legislation.
Language skills must be demonstrated both for the receipt and the extension of the work permit.
Exceptions apply only to citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
Also exempt from this law are persons who received their training certificates and diplomas before the disintegration of the USSR in 1991.
Sense, problem and protection of rights
All the examination bodies will be under the aegis of the Pushkin Institute for Russian Language, the Russian University of Friendship of Nations, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
The migrants can take the tests in all cities; more than 160 centres have already been opened in Russia.
The initiative to introduce the tests was supported by the deputies of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Authority.
Civil rights activists, on the other hand, asked the press several times before the law came into force: What does this bring?
What changes does the requirement to have language skills bring to both the Russians and the guest workers?
Above all, migration officials say, it is about reducing the number of forced labourers.
“Many are now talking about protecting the rights of migrant workers,” said Viktor Sebelev, head of the Federal Migration Agency’s Tajikistan representation.
However, your rights must be protected before they leave.
Only an organized recruitment will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
Migrants without a job, education, language skills and medical assessment face problems.
Sebelev is convinced that a future migrant without language skills will inevitably encounter people with evil intentions, who under the pretext of aid put him in a dark, narrow barracks, where he will endure with dozens of his peers for months without food and documents and create 12 to 14 hours a day.
We receive a lot of complaints from our migrants.
"At home you will be promised the One, and on arrival you will be cheated, get your passports taken off, and do not receive the promised salary," confirms the head of the Labour Migration Administration of the Tajik Migration Authority, Tolib Sharipov.
Don't blaspheme, boss!
Nevertheless, many citizens of the Central Asian republics, who want to make their money in Russia, admit that not only do they not master the language of the target country, but they can hardly express themselves in their own language in writing.
Of course, this is not so much their fault, but rather the evil: only a few Turkmens, Uzbeks and Tajiks can afford even a reasonable elementary education.
Because in their families there is not even money to feed the children, let alone buy them decent clothes, shoes and school supplies.
As teenagers, these children immediately take the first opportunity to earn money.
"It's difficult without language skills," they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
Civil rights activists emphasize the following important aspect of the law.
Only immigrants with legal status must take the test.
If you do not have this status, there is no examination and therefore no official work.
Meanwhile, most of the guest workers continue to be illegal in Russia.
"Welcome" or "Not allowed for unauthorized access"
Many migrants confirm that it is not easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason is bureaucratic hurdles and, of course, linguistic difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
A fake registration can be made quickly and only for one and a half thousand.
The Russian police officers know that our documents are mostly fake and we are not registered, and this results in cases of blackmail.
"They want one or two hundred rubles for cigarettes and tea," Tajik Umed Hushkadamov told reporters.
“Don’t pay for fake papers.”
Already on the day the law came into force, it turned out that not only the registration documents of migrants can be counterfeit.
Some counterfeit certificates that certify the completion of the language test have already been seized by employees of the Federal Migration Agency.
The fake papers were printed with an ordinary color printer.
Of course, the new owners received it not for nothing: every migrant who hoped to avoid the tests in this way paid seven thousand rubles for the document.
That’s more than twice the cost of the official test: it costs a migrant three thousand rubles.
Both officials and civil rights activists agree that the main immediate task is to protect the system from corruption so that the certificates cannot be bought easily.
For the moment, the authorities can only promise that they will get time for a basic language course.
In addition, newcomers without language skills are offered positions in areas where active communication with people is not necessary.
The Ministry of the Interior ignores the illegal arms market
Extremely low share of legal weapons in crime
The Russian Ministry of the Interior is planning a tightening of the Weapons Act for private gun owners.
The authorities responded to recent events: wounded in wedding shootings and seven dead in the assassination of Moscow lawyer Dmitry Winogradov.
Police want to ban the wearing of non-lethal weapons in public and raise the age for possession of firearms from 18 to 21 years.
Irina Jarowaja, chair of the Duma Committee on Security and Anti-Corruption, supported the proposal and promised that the amendments to the Arms Act would be presented to the Duma shortly.
Not everyone is satisfied with the fact that the Russian authorities want to fight the problems by "attracting the screws".
An open letter was published on the internet, whose authors - representatives of various arms associations - demanded that the authorities distance themselves from "senseless intensifications".
The percentage of crimes committed with registered weapons is very low, said the criminal prosecutor, Wasily Lesnikov, the Russian service of the BBC.
According to the statistics of the Ministry of the Interior, 142 crimes with the use of registered weapons were committed in the course of six months in 2012, while a total of 1,168 thousand crimes were recorded for the same period.
The authors of the open letter are convinced that a tightening of the law for private gun owners will not stop criminals from using the black market.
Currently, according to the authors, any weapon can be found in Moscow for little money.
Meanwhile, the Interior Ministry stresses that the distribution of illegal weapons is under control.
Suppliers: from factories to officers
The weapons enter the black market through several channels.
There are five such main channels, says a former Colonel Viktor Baranez, who served for ten years in the Ministry of Education and the General Staff.
Screenshot of a website accepting weapons orders
The first channel is the army or military, i.e. weapons that were stolen during the fighting in the Caucasus.
“The weapons were stolen by both the Russian officers and the Caucasians themselves,” Baranez said.
On the second channel are illegal weapons that are stolen by criminals.
Baranez explains that this includes weapons that have been stolen from both the police’s armory and directly from law enforcement officials.
Other illegally sold weapons come from military weapons warehouses.
In many military camps there were often explosions.
“There is evidence that some cases were firefighting to cover up the lack of weapons,” the former military official said.
According to Baranez, arms manufacturers also contribute to the black market.
“Today, there are countless private armaments factories that cannot withstand international competition and therefore waste their weapons at hand on the black market, for example in Moscow,” the expert reports.
Another channel of the black market is smuggling.
Especially many guns and guns come from poor countries such as Kyrgyzstan.
"There is an own, sometimes artisanal production and a mafia that organizes the smuggling," he said.
Where did the weapons come from?
Experts calculated how much each of the five channels roughly contributed to the supply of illegal weapons to the black market.
In 2011, a report was prepared by the Center for Problem Analysis and State Administration.
The experts analyzed reports from the Ministry of the Interior and the Federal Service for State Statistics, criminological literature and publicly available data on weapons portals.
According to investigators, the vast majority of illegal weapons come from the army and the prosecution authorities.
Half of all guns on the black market have come through the “debt of those responsible who have been dealing with guns in their work,” the report said.
According to data from the researchers, 17% of weapons come from conflict areas, 14% are due to gun theft, and 5% come from illegal excavations.
A sales consultant at an arms store, who does not want to be named by name, assures that weapons found in illegal excavations have long since been bought by no one because they are outdated.
According to him, it is more common for traders to get supplies in an arms warehouse.
A weapon, for example a TT type gun, is purchased via a flag.
The weapon is issued and passed through the fence.
"The dealer brings the gun to the city and sells it there for 900 euros per piece with two magazines," he says.
“Of course, the police know everything and therefore, if they are unable to comply with the crime detection plan, periodically carry out control purchases from dealers who offer illegal weapons,” the sales adviser added.
"Like in the luxury shop"
Buyers and sellers often find acquaintances with each other.
I had watched websites and blogs when someone became aware of me and suggested to come to the station "Begowaja" where a person would be waiting for me to take me to a certain place where we could then negotiate the price.
The price of the gun was only there.
Military commentator Viktor Baranez
"To get a gun, I need a friend who has contacts," says the sales consultant. "I have such a friend, but I don't trust him."
There are traders in the markets, but there you have to go and date with a code such as "by Ivan Ivanovich, who has aligned that the daughter has lost a tooth".
I’m even talking about a friend I trust.
He also gives me the beating rings just because he knows I'm not whistling him.
Newcomers are looking for weapons in different ways.
Former military member Viktor Baranez tried to buy illegal weapons in the mid-1990s when he wrote an article on the subject.
According to him, the schemes have not changed.
