Researchers from the University of California, Berkeley, prove that if the company raised the average wage to $12 an hour, it would cost Walmart $3.2 billion.
That’s about 1.1% more than they donate for wages now.
If Walmart completely converted the wage increases to customers, every purchase would cost them only 46 cents more in the future.
For them, that would be overspending of just $12.39 per year compared to today.
Proponents of Walmart are pleased to note that only nine states protested and did not inflict any losses on the company.
Black Friday lasted in its store from 8 p.m. on Thursday until midnight the next day, and during that period Walmart sold about 5,000 items per second.
In total, Walmart cash registers carried out nearly 100 million transactions on Black Friday.
