"The brain can only be moderately deceived"
The theme of advanced reality, popular with modern technology fans, is usually perceived by the lens of special glasses lately.
Google first presented a working model in the summer at its annual conference, then in November it became known that Microsoft had also applied for a corresponding patent.
In conversation with the head of the group for interactive 3D technologies at the Microsoft laboratory in Cambridge, Shahram Izadi, it becomes clear that the glasses were only a transit station for the company’s scientists.
It stimulates the ability to manipulate virtual objects in the air with bare hands and create virtual open spaces.
- Please describe briefly what research your group is conducting.
- We are dealing with the interaction of humans and machines, but we want to expand the boundaries of this interaction.
So far, most of humanity has been stuck in the phase of working with pixels on flat screens that are sometimes touched.
However, we want to look forward to 5-10 years and predict the radical changes in this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors are a step forward, and nowadays, no Xbox is being sold without Kinect, as everyone is interested in motion control.
- What else can we expect in the future?
Although Kinect has brought the interaction to a physical level, a lot is still happening on the flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The input of information (the system gets more data) has been improved, the output has not yet been decisive.
We are trying to change that by working on real three-dimensional display systems based on different technologies, including projections.
We need to release the computer world into our physical world and make it more tangible.
However, it is necessary that not only the user, but also his environment is recognized.
Then we could complement the real world much easier with virtual objects.
And first of all, we should get rid of these stupid virtual reality helmets!
- What do you think about voice control?
It’s popular, but isn’t it overrated?
- It is certainly not the universal solution, as it raises questions about privacy, because you do not always want to inform all those around about his actions and intentions.
Actually, any type of interaction with computers is good, but each in its specific niche.
For example, in the area of controlling objects in public places, we worked on a project in which we experimented with short and short rather than outgoing gestures.
The gestures were not recorded by the object camera, but by a bracelet that recorded the movements of the bones and muscles.
It is still relatively large, but could theoretically be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
But overall, however, the future belongs to mixed types of control, for example gesture and language.
- What do you mean?
- We'd ask you, for example, to give you this bubble can?
They say it and point to it at the same time.
- Usually I just say it.
- Oh, that would be very hard to see.
- Does that mean you want the user to adapt to what a machine can and can't afford at any given time?
- Not necessarily, but this is about a mutual rapprochement.
I think that in the next few years we will have to work primarily on the development of new types of sensors that will allow us to capture people’s reactions more accurately.
These can be laser sensors, for example, since they offer a good resolution at depth, which is very important.
- What are your demands based on working with Xbox Kinect sensors on modern cameras?
Is there a lack of resolution, depth or something else?
- The current generation is basically a good starting point for our work in the field of three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, 8 megapixels at a speed of 1000 fps would not be bad.
But the main thing is not the megapixels themselves, but the quality of the matrix and the depth.
From this point of view, all current technologies are not good enough for us, as the developers of the algorithms have more work to do.
It is necessary to take into account not only the resolution along the X and Y, but also along the Z axis.
The speed and the number of images per second are also important.
The movements of man are extremely dynamic and frankly, the current 30 fps are insufficient, especially for gestures.
In our lab in Redmond, Stephen Betishes developed a touch sensor with a adjustable processing delay of 1 to 100 milliseconds, with today’s commercial sensors closer to the second (60 to 100).
Not everyone understands how much this affects the interaction between humans and machines.
For my work, I needed a device like this, just without touch control and with more images per second.
- Shouldn't the number of cameras be increased?
- Kinect currently works with three "cameras", one of which is actually an infrared transmitter and the second is a receiver for the reflected signal.
And the third camera is actually an ordinary RGB camera.
It is not used to calculate the object depth.
More cameras might solve the problem...
Or increase the problem, as more calculations would be needed.
It would be nice to have a flexible, Kinect-like system where we could play with different camera inclinations to see how that helps us in the three-dimensional determination of a position.
- Unlike Google, Microsoft did not present its glasses to the public.
Don’t you think that in terms of applying advanced reality technology in everyday life, glasses have the best prospects?
- Of course, it is not pleasant to always hold a smartphone in the raised hand on the road, but I think this: the most great variant would be a "changing" extended reality, in which we could switch from the glasses to the smartphone via a cloud,
The glasses are a personal gadget and this is their strength (only you can see private ones), but at the same time also their weakness, because an extended reality using glasses prevents you from working on virtual objects together with others.
- Let's imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holograms in the air is accessible not only to Tony Stark from Iron Man, but also to normal mortals.
There is a problem that critics of this idea often point out: there is no tangible reaction!
The hands feel nothing at all!
What answers does your group want to give to this objection?
- In my lectures I often talk about that the extended reality represents the seventh breakthrough in the interaction between man and machine.
I think the eighth breakthrough might well be the integration of tactile perception.
An interesting method is currently using the second hand as a somewhat unusual projection support.
She perceives pressure excellently!
However, there are also technologies that are actually designed to give the "pictures in the air" something hand-held, for example, the interference of some directed ultrasound beams at a certain point where the finger is located, creates a feeling that is currently as weak as if someone was blowing over the handballs.
There are also ligaments for the wrist that act on the nerve endings in the fingers, too, which is a potential direction.
- Did you try to deceive the brain?
It makes you think it feels what it should feel when it sees something?
- That's a good idea, so we haven't tried it yet.
Here is another task that we will have to struggle with for a long time, namely to make a person who is physically in a closed space think he is instead in an open, virtually infinite space; here we work on concepts with treadmills (other than in gyms), moving platforms and large balls.
Until now, the brain can only be moderately deceived, and we still have many busy years ahead of us.
This is precisely what makes the work in the field of virtual reality so attractive to a researcher: We are only at the beginning of many topics.
