Birth in space
Earth in danger.
Earth warming or collision with killerasteroid.
Caravans of spaceships with Earth-dwellers on board go on a search for a replacement planet.
In order to save humanity, the important question arises how we can reproduce in weightlessness or on the substitute planet?
In my opinion, there are not many choices.
In fact, there are only two real planets that we could at least hypothetically inhabit.
“Mars and Venus,” says the researcher at the Astronomical Sternberg Institute, Vladimir Surdin.
However, while conditions on Mars are comparatively life-friendly, there is a temperature of 500 degrees on the surface of Venus.
Life would only be possible at high altitude or in the orbit of Venus, i.e. in space.
The question of reproduction in space was first addressed by the researchers with regard to flora.
Already half a century before, experiments were conducted with plants.
The fourth generation of peas grown in orbit did not differ in the least of the earthly species.
This was followed by the breeding of insects, more precisely tiny fruit flies (Drosophila), in orbit.
In 1979, quail eggs were sent into space to explore how weightlessness affects the development of embryos.
A normal chick develops.
But then the problem begins.
"The problem is that the chick has to find a hold; it has to be able to stand on its legs and start moving," explains the laboratory director of the Institute of Medical-Biological Problems RAN, Vladimir Sychev.
Without a solid surface, the chicks overflowed wildly.
Ten hours later, the instincts of the newborns completely blurred.
The chicks did not respond to light and noise.
Four days later, they just died.
"Twice we hatched chicks and then put the whole thing in place because it's simply impossible to work with them there," says Vladimir Sychev about the failed experiment with the chicks in space.
The last breeding cage with animals flew into orbit 16 years ago.
The experiments will continue in the spring of 2013.
However, only same-sex species will be found on the biosatellite "Bion".
There was an experiment with rats that were already fertilized into space.
In principle, nothing special was found.
"That was just with the biosatellites, but again it was just a single experiment, and the research needs to be continued," says Vladimir Sychev.
After landing, the space rats were given offspring.
The problem of reproduction directly in space has not been solved so far.
The task is difficult.
Animals that are torn out of their natural habitat simply cannot follow their reproductive drive.
Unlike animals, humans can do this in principle.
Homo sapiens is capable of abstract thinking and can create a similar emotional background.
For ethical reasons, such experiments are not carried out.
Women have been flying into space for 50 years.
The greatest risk was at Tereshkova.
The most valuable thing that humanity possesses is the female organism.
Our seagull flew away, and no one on Earth could have answered the question: Does it survive the space flight?
Will she be able to give birth after this flight?
"Finally, no one answered this question," says space veteran Wachtang Watschnadse.
In June 1964, just a year after her space flight, the first female cosmonaut, Valentina Tereshkova, gave birth to a daughter.
The child's father, Andrijan Nikolayev, was also a cosmonaut.
In 1988, the second woman in space, Swetlana Sawizkaja, who was in orbit twice and even did work outside the spacecraft, gave birth to a son.
Nevertheless, there is still a risk.
We have very few cosmonauts where everything went well after long flights and they got healthy offspring.
"The more, the more dangerous it is even when flying in orbit," concludes Cosmonaut Waleri Polyakov, hero of the Soviet Union and hero of the Russian Federation.
Yet humanity must look for new ways in biotechnology, radiation protection, and the creation of artificial gravity.
The hydrolaboratory at the Cosmonaut Preparation Centre is a mandatory station during flight preparation.
Here in a floating state, the cosmonauts gain routine for work in open space.
Water represents weightlessness.
Even if adults feel water is pleasant, it is a strange environment; but infants feel water as a natural element.
It is as if the little Ichtyanders are witnessing that life on land came out of the ocean.
There is a connection between the fact that a child is in the mother's womb for about 9 months in the amniotic water, and that he can then more easily get used to water.
In principle, this is logical, since from birth to the first swimming only 2 weeks pass.
"This is not enough time to forget something," says baby swimming instructor Marina Aksenova.
So, while for a newborn child, weightlessness is a much more natural condition, the woman does not get away with gravity.
In the state of weightlessness, the abdominal and pelvic muscles regress enormously quickly and thus also decreases the ability to squeeze the child out.
All right, let's bypass this with birth-inducing tools.
For example, the birth could also take place in a special chamber to squeeze the child out.
"But what happens then?" is the not insignificant question of Waleri Polyakov.
On the other hand, the child also needs artificial gravity.
Without feeling the formation of the earth, the organism cannot train the skeleton and muscles.
A newborn child cannot be put in an exercise suit in orbit like an adult for training.
He will simply lack what is of elementary importance to his life.
"This experiment we are doing together, namely the birth of a child in a foreign environment, will lead to the birth of a disabled person, a completely unsuitable person," predicts the head of the Bioethics Commission of the Institute of Medical-Biological Problems RAN, Igor Pestow.
Until now, the birth of children in space is mere theory.
At some point, however, it will become a reality when the Earth’s inhabitants in their spaceships depart to a distant planet that will become the home for their descendants born in space.
