Do you see the adoption of this law more positively, or will the system be burdened with further bureaucracy?
I think this law is definitely a step in the right direction and I hope that this assumption will be confirmed.
However, the problem may arise that the rules become "stricter" and can no longer be adhered to.
In accordance with the previous rules, persons subjected to an examination are already accountable to the institution (for example, in the case of an operational programme of regional policy, the Regional Council) in that any non-compliance with the Procurement Act amounts to a violation of budgetary discipline.
Does it make sense to tighten the law even more?
In my opinion not in this way.
The system must exclude those who want to attack and abuse the system, and not punish those who have made a form error that does not affect the actual decision-making.
Such a system merely puts even greater pressure on the bureaucracy.
Where's the way out?
First of all, let’s say which path is not good.
The Prime Minister recently said that the ODS would not obstruct entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called "black system" - what exactly does that mean?
Is the black system prohibited or allowed?
A law must have its validity, and if something is prohibited by law, then it cannot simply come to the president of the government, and the control office, whose duty it is now to control compliance with the law, hinders its activity.
He can say, "We're changing the law and allowing the thing," but he can't say we're pretending to be nothing.
The procurement law contains relatively strict rules on the formal execution of certain transactions - and this is also correct for the protection of public competition.
On the other hand, it is also tragic if the tenderer with the best offer is excluded solely due to form errors.
The law will never be perfect, but it must be applied properly - and that is what I think is missing from us.
