Next year we would also like to perform at the Czech House in New York, and I personally - if we are in the USA then - would like to combine this with performances in Washington and Chicago.
Your plans abroad are not very small, so far you have already appeared in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
However, The Tap Tap is a group of people with disabilities.
How do you handle these trips logistically and organizationally?
It’s not as bad as it seems at first glance.
Five of our members are wheelchair users, i.e. the wheelchairs must be transported in the luggage compartment. In addition, we must of course carry many instrument cases and other luggage...
Nevertheless, it has always worked without problems so far, <0xC4><0x8C>SA and British Airways were always very well prepared for us, that I have sometimes already wondered.
Even in Moscow, where we were recently, there were no problems.
Through your travel abroad you have a comparison of what it looks like in the individual countries with accessibility, how to deal with disabled people there, etc.
How have you experienced these things so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other cities where everything works better than with us, we just witnessed in Russia that everything in the East is still in its beginnings.
In Prague, Moscow is absolutely not handicapped, where it is still unusual for someone to travel in a wheelchair alone in the city centre.
It is not even self-evident there that a wheelchair user is allowed in the elevator, for example.
Fortunately, there are also associations that try to point out the problems of people with disabilities.
And in what ways do we have to catch up with the more developed countries?
There are still a lot of things we hang out after...
However, it should also be noted that an improvement in the situation always depends on the efforts of those affected.
In London and Madrid, it is absolutely common for people with severe disabilities to move independently in the public space, go to the museum, use toilets, etc.
But it is not exactly common for a larger group of disabled people to be actively involved in the social events, in this we are a little ahead of the West with the band The Tap Tap!
Public respect and accessibility is one thing, but only when important athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers come from our ranks will things really start to change.
So far, these are only individual cases of particularly willing personalities.
The Tap Tap is very popular right now, but if we go back a few years, what motivated you to start a band in 1998?
At that time I started as a mentor at the Jedli<0xC4><0x8D>ka Institute, where I met many young people who were interested in dealing with something intensely.
