Poland and space.
Last week, Poland was admitted as the twentieth member of the European Space Agency at a meeting of the Ministerial Council of the member states of the European Space Agency ESA, making it the second member of the former Eastern bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a member of ESA on 12 November 2008).
Poland began a close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and participated in several ESA projects in the following years.
Poland’s journey into space began much earlier.
Even before the Second World War, Polish cosmos enthusiasts engaged in space travel, not always encountering understanding.
I recall, for example, A. <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld’s talk of 6 December 1933 at the Warsaw Observatory, in which the author presented thoughts from his pioneering work “Entrance to Cosmonautics”.
However, the ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the audience cold, and after years <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld still remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski had shown interest in his work.
In 1934, <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld won the Prix REP deer funded by Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch for "Entrance to Cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became an important advocate of astronomy and space travel.
In Polish journals he published hundreds of articles and wrote several books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomsky’s world-renowned contribution to the development of space has been honored, among other things, by having one of the craters on the earth-facing side of the moon named after him.
Already in 1925 a railway draisine was built in Poland, for which a rocket drive was planned.
Unfortunately, the author of the draft and the details of this project remained unknown.
It is not even clear whether the rocket should be used for launching or braking the Draisine.
The information in this regard comes exclusively from the contemporary press.
In 1933, the Polish infantry began to deal with missile-powered missiles.
The research was conducted by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzyckiegi.
It can be seen from the surviving documents that the research had advanced to the stage of practical tests.
The research was interrupted by the invasion of the German Wehrmacht.
In 1937, a photoelectric rocket design by Rohozi<0xC5><0x84>ski appeared in the trade press, and the following year the work "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocky appeared.
Both projects dealt with the military use of the missile propulsion.
Shortly before the war, all projects for the military use of missile technology were coordinated by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Committee Doradczo-Naukowy).
The committee was established in 1937, but after two years of activity, its work was terminated by the beginning of the war.
Further articles on space were published in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Space Company (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The first mention of this society is made in the November issue of the journal Problemy in 1954, in which four extensive articles are devoted to space.
The article by Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal for the creation of a space company.
At the time, there were already the first projects on satellite technology, and it was expected that space exploration would have a future.
In its inception in 1956, the Polish Space Company PTA endeavoured to join the International Federation for Space, founded in 1951, and in fact, the PTA became a full member in the autumn of 1956.
The following year, the first PTA Chairman, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became Deputy Chairman of the International Federation for Space.
He held this office until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has been instrumental in the development of the extremely successful meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), the first Polish rocket for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, the first launch took place on 10 October 1958.
The rocket with a maximum flight height of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and weighed not quite 5 kg.
Later, an improved version, the RM-1A, was built, and in 1959 began flight tests in the B<0xC5><0x82><0xC4><0x99>dów Desert with the two-stage missile RM-2.
The rocket was 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another stage of development should already be able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should reach a flight height of up to 14.5 km and be used for observing altitude winds.
In 1962, however, further development was discontinued.
The successor to the first RM-type rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket developed in 1962 to 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage missile, its total length was 510 cm and the launch weight was 32.5 kg.
From this rocket three types were developed (Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed from each other in the size of the transport space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a transport space with a capacity of 0.4 liters, Meteor-1B over 0.34 liters and Meteor-1C over 0.62 liters.
The maximum altitude of all three types was 37 km.
From 1965 to 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Aviation Institute, whose first flight tests began in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had a starting weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a payload of 10 kg to an altitude of about 60 km.
After that, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
Also worth mentioning is Poland’s accession to the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960, which was followed two years later by the establishment of a national COSPAR committee.
Poland also participated in space research with Soviet satellites, and in 1978 Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became second intercosmonaut after Czech Vladimír Remek.
Repealing the Non-Profit Work Act is not a solution.
Last week, the constitutional court lifted the law on non-profit work.
This decision sparked a lively public discussion.
It is certainly interesting to look at the problem from a broader perspective.
Liberal economic systems in the EU and in the globalised world are based on the principle of unregulated economic competition.
In the end, this means that the individual economies are in permanent conflict with each other.
The reason for this is the principle of free trade and the free, unrestricted movement of private capital, which goes hand in hand with unrestrained financial speculation.
Due to the large differences in the value of work (wages), there are price tensions.
This term is to be understood as a condition in which the manufacturer tries to maintain economic competitiveness by importing favourable goods by "undercutting" the competition in order to seize a greater market share and thereby increase his profit.
On a large scale, this means for most companies to move their production abroad or buy cheaply there, or to give up their business. The result is high unemployment in countries with similarly high labour costs.
Since private capital bears no social responsibility and thus no responsibility for the unemployment caused by it, government spending necessarily increases.
This situation is further exacerbated by the fact that the entrepreneurs are absolutely unwilling to pay their taxes and thus to compensate for the economic and social damage caused by them as a whole.
This situation is generally known, so that concrete statistics are superfluous at this point.
The reckless practice of private capital creates a situation in the individual economies in which governments are forced to compete with each other in order to artificially lower the social level of their own population and thus attract foreign capital into the country.
In other words, governments supply their own populations to private capital regardless of the social consequences.
This is reflected in particular in amendments to applicable laws.
The aim of these measures is to force the own population to accept the dictate of private capital, especially in the wage sector.
This is done on the one hand by economic coercion in the case of long-term unemployment, on the other hand by the circumcision of workers' rights.
The result is growing poverty, as well as ever-increasing differences between rich and poor.
For some years now, there have been public food outlets in Germany for poor people who are no longer able to feed themselves through their own work.
The number of people affected is already in the millions.
In the course of increasing the competitiveness of the German economy, there are regularly cases in which workers receive such a low wage that the state has to increase their income to the minimum of existence.
Such a scandal was also revealed in the case of aid workers employed in the German Bundestag.
The austerity measures of virtually all EU southern states will undoubtedly result in the same state in which people are forced to emigrate under the pressure of a catastrophic crash of their social level (as was the case in the 19th century), or to starve for a wage on the margins of society, hoping that at some point private investment capital will flow into the country.
The question is, of course, where does this capital come from?
If it comes from another EU country, poverty only migrates from one country to another; or the capital remains completely out, because in China, India, Brazil, Turkey, Morocco or Egypt, or even in Africa, the workers work for a fraction of the European wages.
This applies to all of Latin America.
Liberal theories and media claim, to the point of overwhelming pressure, that the state is not allowed to participate in its own economy with capital, and that plan economy leads to economic catastrophe.
Private capital firmly insists on its position that the state must not intervene steeringly in the economy.
But then one has to ask whether private capital does not influence politics and thus the whole state in its own selfish sense or even direct it.
Here is the clear answer: Yes.
The proof of this is the existence of a virtually omnipotent lobby that is ubiquitous in all states.
The result is a desperate situation in the area of corruption, mutual preference, legislation in which practically everything is punishable but nothing criminal.
In Germany, the situation is such that a State Ministry, due to a lack of finance, commissions private, closely intertwined legal companies with the drafting of legislation.
These bills will then be passed in the Bundestag.
All violence then no longer proceeds from the people, as the Western constitutions proclaim, but from strong financial groups that prefer their own interests.
Apparently, the liberal democracies are now quickly in a situation as Appian describes it in his work on the crisis of the Roman Republic at the time of Caesar and Pompeius: "The state has long been in disintegration, and the offices have been filled with violence.
Against lubrication, by unlawful exploitation of advantages, or with stone and sword.
"People with character did not apply for office, so that, as a result of this decline, the state did not have a strong consul for eight months" ... "They began to really talk about the fact that the only medicine in this difficult situation was a solitary rule, and that a strong man the C<0xC3><0xB4>me was to be elected to...
As it turns out, today’s society, as in antiquity, is based on the reckless preference of one’s own advantage, without paying attention to the interests of society as a whole.
Private capital is already by its very nature unable to recognize and enforce the advantage for society as a whole.
The result, today as at the time, is an unprecedented decadence of elites who are not striving at the slightest for deeper reforms.
We must therefore look for the cause of the rise of fascism and communism in the reckless liberalization of economic systems in the 19th and 20th centuries.
From the present state, the collapse of these regimes in favour of liberal democracies can be seen as a certain break, at which the next round is already taking place.
Especially catastrophic is the fact that today’s elites are in complete ignorance of the possible losses of hundreds of thousands of lives in the future, of the humanitarian and social disasters we are already witnessing today, and of the crimes against humanity as we know it from older and more recent history.
The repeal of the law on non-profit work is not a solution here, at least not a lasting one.
Under pressure from global and European economic competition, the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to look for ways to push down the social level of the population.
This trend is therefore systemic.
The only solution is targeted political and social reforms that increase the state’s participation in the economy, increase the influence of citizens on the government, and weaken the monopoly of private capital in society in favor of the state.
