The movie Argo: If it's the worst, call Hollywood
In November 1979, a mob of demonstrating Islamist students occupied the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
For their release, they demanded the extradition of the overthrown Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who had fled to the United States after the revolution, which had maintained the patronage over his regime for decades.
For the American government there was no positive way out of this situation - it could not afford to throw the shah overboard, as it would have massively damaged the trust of its allies in other countries.
At the same time, it was unable to enforce the release of hostages in Iran, where the revolution led to the establishment of a theocratic regime.
It was a severe blow to the reputation of the United States, and the subsequent fiasco in the violent attempt to liberate the gills only made everything worse.
The captured diplomats were finally released after 444 days after negotiations had been mediated by the Algerian government.
The destiny of the hostages sparked a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiments at home.
The debacle in Iran contributed significantly to the defeat of Jimmy Carter against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo by director and actor Ben Affleck describes an episode of this story that gave the United States a small partial victory.
Immediately before the occupation of the embassy, six embassy officials managed to escape.
This ended after numerous complications in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
The CIA, in collaboration with the Canadian authorities, managed to bring the refugees out of Iran, helping them with an extravagant story to cover up their true identity – they travelled with Canadian passports disguised as members of a film club that allegedly visited locations in the country for a science fiction film.
Combination of genres
The plan developed by “exfiltration” expert Tony Mendez also required Hollywood’s collaboration.
To make the camouflage credible, articles about this film project appeared in specialist journals, press conferences were held, and the fictional production company had a real office.
The details of this operation have been kept secret for a long time. The film is based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck Film is a special combination of several film genres.
On the one hand, he is a realistic political thriller, but at the same time also a so-called "Caper Movie", i.e. the story of a successful hussar piece such as the film Ocean's Eleven.
As a result, the mood levels in the film alternate - on the one hand the documentary scenes from Tehran (in the title sequence, iconic contemporary photographs are shown, and also in the film version of the same situations there are no great differences).
On the other hand, the loose passages from Hollywood, which come ironically and slightly overstated.
And then there are the scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions - men in suits at the meeting table, on the hallways, on the phone...
Ben Affleck made a remarkable reboot of his career with this film.
A smiled actor has become a respectable director, and also as an actor he is no longer the target of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the crime film Gone Baby Gone (2007) and the thriller City Without Grace (2010).
At the same time, it is Affleck’s first film, which is not set in the director’s hometown of Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of the place was one of the characteristics that set this director’s previous films apart from the Hollywood standard.
Affleck, however, also demonstrates this feeling in Argo, where Tehran is "played" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film play in the streets and show the reconstruction of events that really took place - the entrance sequence of the storming of the message is very impressive in its clarity, while still conveying the sense of confusion and unpredictability that occurs when the story moves somewhere.
Affleck and his team achieve a similar effect even in fictional scenes (the wrong film rod on a bazaar in Tehran).
Too much action in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story does not actually offer many scenes that are exciting in the cinematic sense.
But he works quite successfully with the few, sometimes helping the reality - which then does not always look so elegant (the scenes in which the impending crisis at the airport in Tehran is averted from a phone call in America, or even the chase on the runway, seem somewhat artificial).
Argo’s weakness is his too wide spread, which is due to the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in their roles as Hollywood employees, but their characters deserve more space, and so they are far from alone in the film.
Affleck’s film loses a bit of traction, a film that one can follow with a certain interest, while savouring the design and the retro style reminiscent of a thriller from the 70’s.
But it is hard to awaken enthusiasm.
However, as a reminder of a piece of history that is still alive to this day, and as proof of how exaggerated the ideas of the almighty and all-knowing intelligence services are, it is sufficient.
