The MVRDV architects prove that the true adventures are not only in the mind - on the example of Spijkenisse and the recently erected Bücherberg - 2 photos
“I find the building funny, it looks futuristic, and finally there’s something interesting to see again,” says Lisette Verhaig, a passer-by at the side of the road.
And Stefan Spermon, an IT technician in a nearby large business, says: "But, it's nice, the house."
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
They all have internet, iPad and e-books.
No one goes voluntarily to one of these old-style libraries today, right?
Spijkenisse, a sleeping town barely in need of visitation on the outskirts of Rotterdam, is a strange recordholder.
The 80,000-dwelling community has the lowest education rate in the entire Netherlands.
To counter this stupid circumstance, a few years ago, it was decided to contribute to general education and to reconstruct the seven fictional bridges depicted on the euro banknotes as beautifully brushed concrete miniatures.
The success of the educational offensive was limited.
And so the city fathers realized that there was only one way to master the statistics: a library must come!
Winy Maas of the Rotterdam architecture firm MVRDV, master of bold beam diagrams and producer of funny, often cynical buildings, took the matter with the usual serenity and appeared at the competition hearing in 2003 with five books under his arm and a smile on his face.
And while the jury was still looking around and shrugging with its arms, the naughty Maas stacked his exquisite pieces of magnitude into a pyramid and ended his action-based speech with the words: "Dear city community!"
So this is my proposal for the Book Mountain of Spijkenisse, for the so-called Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the 30 million euro mountain has been spilled.
It is part of a revitalization project, which includes underground parking, supermarket, post office and a few adjacent residential and semi-detached houses with a total of 50 apartments.
In early November, the Buchenberg was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
The project is also nominated for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
Thus, the faceless small town retort, which until now had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian zone and a staggeringly ugly town hall, behind whose white facades one would be inclined to suspect a dairy factory to a piece of contemporary architecture richer.
Above all, however, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural structure in the history of its existence.
The long way to the book
The first impression: Bookeldorado under cheese bell.
There is a lift that leads through the middle of the mountain massif, but the true pleasures of space and reading are unlocked by the walking climb of the topography.
The all-glazed interior is bright and clear, the burned clinker floor and the elegant street lights speak unmistakably the language of a public square.
The urban environment is perfect.
One is already looking for park bench, dog and football playing boys and girls.
And everywhere books, books, books.
“Normally the bookshelves are along the fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade, and in the middle is a large, dark room, which is usually uncomfortable and impersonal,” says Winy Maas.
We have turned the classic room configuration upside down and squeezed the reading area from the inside out.
The interior of the Bucherberg is cleverly used: in the middle are offices, internet library, chess club, environmental center and house technology center.
A special pleasure are the black bookshelves, which are sometimes wall coverings, sometimes breasting, sometimes stair railings.
Look, feel and smell are strange.
Even embossed architects and civil engineers shake their heads over the unknown building material.
"We wanted to work with recycling materials here," explains Joop Trouborst, project manager at Spijkenisse, at the request of the standard.
And so one day we found a suitable waste product from agriculture in a Frisian farm.
For many years in the Netherlands, a millimeter-thin plastic fleece has been used as a root base in greenhouses and fields.
This is cheap and time-efficient.
The thin textile lasts one, two seasons, after which it is ripe for the locked garbage.
For the library, the fleece - for the first time in these quantities - was pressed to four centimeters thick plates.
Under heat and pressure, the so-called Landbouwplastic (KLP) discolors into a dark, homogeneous, durable material that smells like new cars and sports shoes.
After 105 steps you reach the summit.
At the end of the almost 500-metre-long hike you will be rewarded in the literary café not only with a fantastic view of the city, but also with Dutch croquettes and stuffed ficus trees.
They provide for the atmosphere, but above all for the right humidity in the literary mountains.
Donations for the new soul
"You wouldn't believe it, but despite the many glass surfaces, this house is a flagship project in terms of ecology," says Trouborst.
Heat and cool with geothermal heat.
Although the Bucherberg is under a glass fall, even on sunny days the sun shines only briefly inside.
The wide wooden glue binders, which are transverse to the glass fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade, serve as shading and capture much of the sunlight.
The indoor climate is very pleasant.
The rest is done by fully automatic shutters.
Stefan Spermon, the initial sceptic from the IT industry, already ventured into the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was there too.
And also the TCM teacher Cynthia Bogarde, who even refers to the Boekenberg as Spijkenisses "latest overdue soul".
The reason: to open a few weeks ago, each resident was invited to donate a book from his personal stock.
For the time being, the optical gaps in the library - currently 70,000 pieces - are to be filled.
The concept has emerged.
The shelves are filled to the top.
“Nothing is worse than a half-empty library,” says architect Winy Maas.
"I think thanks to our invitation, every resident now has a certain relationship with this new house.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
And if it's just for adornment.
With this, MVRDV has succeeded in achieving that royal discipline, which is called in the technical jargon identity foundation.
Spijkenisse has written literature history.
As young and uneducated as she may be.
This is finally a starting point for identity.
Szabo: "Germans need to play a bigger role"
Germany abstained in the vote on the inclusion of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on U.S.-European relations, Berlin is balancing it on a narrow diplomatic level.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany had initially signalled that it would vote against the request for observer status of Palestinians at the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained.
Why did you?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis did in Gaza.
Now, however, Germany has to be cautious because of its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I do not believe it supports the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained when it came to establishing a no-fly zone.
This was eventually enforced by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on important international issues?
Yeah, that's right.
This is because it is turning its foreign policy around, away from a policy that was managed by the US, so to speak, towards a German foreign policy.
What is more, the Europeans do not have a coherent and unified policy.
So the Germans find themselves between the fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they’re still tapping into their role, but they’re on their way to a more “normal” foreign policy.
A foreign policy like France or Britain.
What does a “normal” foreign policy mean in concrete terms from the German point of view?
It shows the willingness to take positions independent of those of the US or European partners in national interests.
I believe that German foreign policy is motivated by economic policy, i.e. by exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany’s economic interests are to a certain extent different from those of the other major powers and therefore Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the attitude in the Middle East conflict and the UN vote?
On the one hand, Germany has large sales markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf states.
That is why it is necessary to be careful not to beat the public, but also the elites, in the Arab countries.
That definitely plays a role.
But I wouldn’t want to put too much weight on it either, it’s not a completely one-sided relationship.
But it definitely plays an important role in German considerations.
Has Germany damaged its relations with the United States by abstaining from voting on important decisions, such as the vote on Palestine?
I believe that there is a great understanding of the German position in Europe and even in the United States.
That is why I do not believe that this was such a dramatic break as in the Libyan question.
Perhaps Germany will even have some respect for it.
Because it signals that it must be taken seriously as an international player and its interests must be taken into consideration.
There are different opinions in Europe about the Palestinian initiative.
The United States has clearly voted for a veto.
Are there disagreements between the United States and many European nations?
Because of American domestic policy, these differences have always existed.
I think the administration under Obama secretly has a fair amount of understanding of the European position.
But due to the political situation here, of course, the government cannot publicly represent this position.
I think the actual disagreements are not as great as they always seem.
If you look at the relations between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, then Obama is not so enthusiastic about Netanyahu’s politics.
Is it difficult for Germany to agree its close relations with Israel and the US on the one hand, and the position of the main partners in the EU on the other?
I think that’s what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and unified European policy, which is not currently the case.
So they can’t be part of a broader line and instead have to push things out of their own position.
This is what they are doing with the euro.
I believe that in the future Germany will take a leading role in pushing Europe to a European position.
Of course, this is not easy for Germany, even because of the relationship with Israel.
