On Twitter, he accused Mursi's supporters of wanting to lead a "coup against democracy".
"If he proclaims the referendum, we will go to his palace and overthrow him," said opposition leader Jasser Said.
"We are not tired yet, the blood of our brothers is not yet atoneed," Egyptian media quoted opposition politician Chaled Ali as saying.
And several judges announced that they did not want to oversee the referendum, which would render it invalid.
“The Qur’an is our Constitution.”
The well-organized Muslim Brotherhood, for its part, blew to the counter-demonstration, but as a precaution not on Tahrir Square, but after a mass prayer on the other river in front of the Cairo University.
Many veiled women and followers of the Salafists participated in it, shouting, “The people demand the application of God’s law.”
They demanded of Mursi: "Clean the land!" and proclaimed: "The Koran is our constitution."
A struggle for sovereignty over the symbolic Tahrir Square, on which everything began, would probably have instigated civil war-like conditions.
It was obvious that Mursi’s supporters didn’t want to risk this.
The Muslim Brotherhood declared that both the opponents of the draft constitution and the supporters had spoken out loud and clear.
Now is the time to let the people at the ballot box decide in which direction the country should go.
A majority for the Islamist draft is considered safe.
“The word human rights doesn’t even exist.
Hafez Abu Saeda is angry at this forced constitutional process, which should have gone by February and involve all social forces.
The 48-year-old human rights lawyer and chairman of the Egyptian Human Rights Organization (EOHR) defended the Muslim Brotherhood while they were in prison or on trial under Mubarak.
Not because he would share their worldview, but because human rights are indivisible to him.
For this he was beaten, convicted, imprisoned.
"And now the word human rights is not even in the new constitution," he laments in a conversation with the "World on Sunday".
Morsi’s expansion of power to all three powers in the state led the lawyer to resign.
These measures are blatant violations of democratic rules of the game and will lead Egypt into a new dictatorship.
“Instead of strengthening civil society, the president de facto overrides it,” Saeda said.
But without civil society organizations, a democracy could not work.
Saeda feels left alone, even by the international community, which considers the ideological struggle of direction on the Nile with a mixture of curiosity and tension.
That could take revenge.
A protester on the Tahrir warns, "You are giving birth to a monster that you can no longer control."
Rakfisk from Norway: Is this the most smelly fish in the world?
Norway’s five million inhabitants enjoy one of the highest standards of living – not only in Europe, but all over the world.
Could the country’s secret of success have something to do with the local appetite for pretty disgusting fish?
Take a selection of overripe cheeses.
Place them in the middle of a pile of dirty, wet sportswear.
And leave her there for a week.
The smell of Rakfisk, one of Norway’s great delicacies, can be imagined.
I am in the small town of Fagernes, about three hours from Oslo.
There is snow here, spectacular landscapes - and that stubborn smell in the air that just doesn't want to disappear.
Rakfisk is salt-sprinkled trout, which, depending on how stinky you would like your fish to be, is fermented in water for up to a year.
When the darkness comes over the country in Norway and the weather gets colder, Norwegians flock to a feast here in Fagernes, which is dedicated to this, well, very brilliant specialty.
"You eat it raw and then rinse it down with a glass of aquavit," says Havard Halvarsen, who actually works at the local fire station, but also hosts the festival as a so-called "Rakfisk General".
People around us eat small fish cubes and consume large amounts of alcohol.
“People like the aquavit more than the rakfisk,” says Havard.
The spirits can displace the smell.
I'm eating a few chops.
Avoiding bringing the Rakfisk near the nose is not bad - like sushi, which has a pretty long bus ride behind it.
Rakfisk is the product of a completely different, far poorer Norwegian era, when there were no cooling facilities yet and fish was soaked in airtight salt water barrels in autumn.
In the deepest winter, it was then removed after long fermentation and consumed - undoubtedly using alcohol-steamed senses.
Even a generation ago, thousands of Norwegians in search of work were forced to leave their country and emigrated mainly to the United States.
Today, the population is growing rapidly – more than 13% are immigrants, attracted by a thriving labour market, high wages and a comprehensive health care system.
Even from Sweden, the old rival, who was far richer than Norway not so long ago, immigrants are pouring in.
Rakfisk is regarded as something important – as an essential, if strictly smelling part of Norwegian history.
It is one of the most expensive dishes you can buy here.
But actually everything is expensive here - a small glass of beer or a sandwich costs proud 10 euros.
Norway doesn’t often make it into the world press, and most people don’t seem to bother it.
Here it is still hated to name Anders Breivik by name – those racist right-wing extremists who shot 77 men, women and children last year.
Instead, it refers only to the "July 22 incident".
Norwegians struggle to accept that someone in their peace-loving country is capable of such brutal murders.
Since the early 1970s, the growth of one of the largest oil and gas industries in the world has been primarily responsible for Norway’s present-day wealth.
“But oil isn’t the only reason we’re doing so well,” says Anna, our waitress who distributes the round trays with mature Rakfisk and embodies the Nordic ideal with her long blonde hair and piercing blue eyes.
We are, as they say, a prudent people.
Their English is impeccable just like most people here.
We're not very brave, we don't like boasting.
Norway has handled its oil wealth very carefully – a large part of the industry’s revenues are invested in a special fund for the benefit of future generations.
When, in the years leading up to the global economic crisis, everyone was throwing around money they didn’t have, Norway kept its wallet tightly closed.
"As long as we can ski in winter and hike in summer, we are happy," says Anna.
"And of course eat Rakfisk," she adds with carefree laughter.
I stand in the snow and prepare for another dish - I have enough of Rakfisk.
Such a moose burger is definitely something else. The juicy meat bites me.
But in the evening the stinkfish is on the menu again.
The hotel I live in is one of several venues that organize a Rakfisk dinner where guests can vote for the best - or perhaps the most challenging - fish.
There is a live TV circuit to a fly-clad showmaster surrounded by plates with Rakfisk.
The show is similar to the Eurovision Song Contest.
"What score do you have up there in the mountains for the best fish, Thor-Jürgen?"
"Here are our points, Havard."
They clap and laugh.
A man falls from his chair, possibly overwhelmed by aquavite.
But perhaps it is the strict haze of the whole fish.
Mexico’s Enrique Pena Nieto faces a difficult start
As Mexico’s future President Enrique Pena Nieto prepares for his inauguration, the BBC’s Will Grant analyzes the challenges ahead and the mixed feelings of his people.
Currently, traffic in Mexico City is particularly bad.
Even on better days, this is a city that is always clogged, but on Monday a steel ring was erected that blocks several important traffic routes to the capital and causes chaos on the streets.
The goal, however, was not to disturb commuters on their way to work, but to prevent protesters from reaching parliament.
On Saturday, Mexico’s new President Enrique Pena Nieto will receive the presidential binding and take over the nation’s leadership.
He is facing a complex task.
Under the incumbent government of Felipe Calderons, Mexico has proven itself economically well, but the country is under the grip of a drug war that has already claimed 60,000 lives in the last six years.
“My government is strongly committed to reducing violence,” Pena Nieto told President Barack Obama earlier this week in the Oval Office.
I will propose a new security strategy with which we can achieve this goal.
Pena Nieto served as the governor of his home state, Mexico, before he went on par with the US president.
In this densely populated, vast part of the country that surrounds the capital, opinions about the new head of state are divided.
A direct man
In the remote small town of Valle del Bravo, for example, one likes to remember him.
Residents of the resort attribute to him the development of tourism and the construction of infrastructure.
To reach the city, you can drive on one of the highways that Pena Nieto built and which represent a great improvement compared to the brittle, bumpy roads that once existed here.
Plaques with his name also hang outside a modern sports center and an impressive interactive museum on climate change.
"We expect him to make real and lasting changes," said his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernandez, who serves as a congressman for the Pena Nietos party, which works for PRI.
In particular, with regard to security and the economy, we hope for an interesting and real change that our country needs so urgently.
After 81 years in power, the PRI was replaced by Vicente Fox in 2000.
Congressman Olvera admits that after 12 years outside the presidential palace of Los Pinos, the party has high expectations of Enrique Pena Nieto.
The opposition’s accusations that the new president lacks substance, he rejects.
He is a very direct man, very committed and has great plans for the country.
He is an excellent statesman, but above all, he is also someone who can listen.
But on the other side of the state, not many people share this view of their former governor.
In Nezahualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Neza, the contrast to the cobbled streets of Valle del Bravo could not be greater.
The place is hidden under highway crossings and in many ways represents a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems in the community are of decisive urban nature.
Earlier this year, the military was deployed to combat drug gangs operating in the neighborhoods, and violence against women is a particularly acute problem.
In the past two years alone, the bodies of dozens of murdered women have been left in a patch of land near a large dump.
During the tenure of Governor Pena Nieto, more than 1,000 women were murdered in the state of Mexico - a statistic that even surpasses that of the city of Ciudad Juarez, which is notorious for their violence and the murders of innocent women.
Critics Pena Nietos believe that he has at least not adequately addressed the problem of women’s murder during his term of office.
But in the worst case scenario, his government closed their eyes to the problem.
In a concrete building, typical of the decayed neighborhood, Irinea Buendia struggles with tears as she shows me photos of her late daughter Mariana Luna.
According to the official version of the events, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
But her family believes she was murdered by her partner.
“When I arrived at her home, it seemed like her body had been washed,” recalls Senora Buendia.
There were signs that she was beaten, and the corpse starch had already set in.
As her mother tells her story, a picture of Mariana looks down on us from the wall. It is attached next to a cross that bears a single word: justice.
But this is exactly what the family has been denied so far.
The authorities treated me as if I were a talker, a troublemaker, a troublemaker.
They want you to simply accept their judgment and keep your mouth shut.
“But that’s not possible if there were so many form errors and omissions,” she says.
When President Pena Nieto receives the Presidential Binding on Saturday, he also assumes a great responsibility.
Tens of thousands of Mexican families have been affected by violent crimes over the past six years, and the new president has promised to take special care of this issue during his term.
“I hope that as president he will be the way he was as governor,” said Olvera, a member of the PRI Congress in Valle del Bravo.
But the families of the victims in Ciudad Neza fear this the most.
Prosecutors say Bradley Manning did not complain about abuse
Prosecutors disagree with Bradley Manning's allegations that he was abused in prison
Hearing deals with Manning's time in military prison in Quantico, Virginia
The defense seeks a rejection of the indictment due to excessive conditions of imprisonment
US Army soldier accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents
The prosecutor's office on Friday attempted to find that Army Brigadier Bradley Manning - charged with the largest disclosure of confidential information in U.S. history - missed several occasions to complain about the alleged mistreatment he suffered in military detention.
During a cross-examination of Manning during a pre-trial hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Maj. Ashden Fein stated that records of weekly visits made by prison officials during Manning’s nine-month imprisonment in Quantico, Virginia, had no complaints about his treatment.
A day before the cross-examination, which was held as a result of a defense request to deny the indictment - Manning had already been sufficiently punished by the hard detention - Manning had testified that he had considered suicide in prison.
The intelligence analyst, who was arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents during his time in Iraq.
The material was then published by WikiLeaks on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed Manning as the source of the information.
At the hearing on Friday, Fein and Manning went through the forms that officers had filled out after their meeting with Manning during his detention in the Quantico Military Prison, where he had been held under tightened detention conditions from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers asked Manning questions and wrote down his answers.
When Fein asked him about the forms on Friday, Manning admitted that he had judged the treatment by his guards to be "excellent" and the treatment by the institution as a whole as "very professional".
The forms, Fein said, did not contain complaints about abuse, even though officials had asked Manning directly about his treatment.
Manning replied that he had expressed his concerns orally and that the officials had discussed them with him and indicated that they would deal with them, but they had not been recorded.
“They wrote down (after discussing the concerns) ‘No problems,’ and that didn’t necessarily mean I didn’t say anything at all,” Manning said.
The judge, Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he did not complain about his treatment when he met with a committee in January 2011 to investigate the suicidal thoughts he mentioned a few months earlier on a form.
Manning replied that his intention during this meeting was to downgrade his observational status to "prevention of injury".
The military said it had assigned him this restrictive status – which is one level under suicidal risk – for his own and the protection of others.
"I wanted to convince employees that I was doing well and get rid of the observational status for injury prevention ... in order to achieve a higher quality of life in my view," Manning said.
Manning testified Thursday that he was arrested and transferred to Kuwait, where he was detained for nearly two months before being transferred to the Quantico Marine Base in Virginia in July 2010.
He said he had considered suicide in Kuwait and was once unconscious due to the heat.
Not being allowed to know what was going on with him or in the outside world was a burden.
"My world shrunk on Camp Arafjon, on this cage," Manning said Thursday.
I thought I'd die in that cage.
When he was moved to Quantico, Manning spent most of his days in a small cell — at least 21 hours and often more than 23 hours — and without company.
He was only allowed a mattress, a blanket, flip flops, clothes and his glasses.
Manning said he tried to stay in motion because it was forbidden to sleep or even lie down during the day.
He always had to sleep with light that penetrated his cell from the outside.
When he turned around at night and guards could no longer see his face, they woke him up to turn back.
In January 2011, Manning’s lawyer formally objected to Manning’s treatment.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to the military prison at Fort Leavenworth, Kansas.
On Friday, Judge Manning also questioned an accusation he had raised in his testimony on Thursday - so he had to sleep a night naked in his cell in Quantico and stand naked at a morning count in front of guards and other prisoners.
Manning had testified that he had never had the opportunity to cover himself with his blanket during this count.
During the interview on Friday, Manning said he had closed an order from his guard that he should have dropped the blanket with which he could have covered himself, but he admitted that no one had asked him to do so.
On Thursday, Manning testified that he was forced to sleep naked the night before, trying to show an official that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning had told the officer that he could have used the waistband of his pants or his flip-flops to hurt himself, but he did not.
That night, Manning said, his pants, flip-flops and glasses were removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account his detention experiences and drastically reduce his imprisonment should he be convicted at his trial in the military court, which is scheduled for early next year.
The defense has stated that Manning will plead guilty to lesser offenses, while other charges that are considered too extreme are to be challenged.
The hearing is scheduled to continue this weekend and the prosecutor is expected to justify the conditions of detention.
The Pentagon remains in its position that Manning has been detained in accordance with the provisions applicable to all inmates held under the highest security precautions in Quantico.
The charges against Manning include favoring the enemy, unlawful disclosure of intelligence on the Internet, transmission of national defense information, and theft of public property or documents.
If he is found guilty on all charges, he will face life imprisonment.
My Mexican-American identity crisis.
Many people are forced to leave Mexico due to lack of opportunities
Mexicans tend to blame the emigrants - they remind them of difficult times, he says
Navarrette believes Mexican Americans are trapped between two worlds
On a recent trip to Mexico City, I had just crossed the hall and had arrived at the passport control when insanity spread within me.
Signs referred to two queues: one for "Mexicanos" ("Mexicans"), another for "Extranjeros" ("Foreigners").
I stood there for a few seconds, unsure to which I should go.
I grew up in Central California and have been called “Mexican” all my life.
An ethnic abbreviation - exactly as my friends in Boston call themselves "Iren" or my friends in New York "Italian".
Later, I chose "Mexican-American".
But this was Mexico.
And in my grandfather’s home there was no need for abbreviations or hyphens.
I was just American.
I speak Spanish, at least good enough to assert myself in this language at both ends of an interview.
But I don’t have the vocabulary of a native speaker, and I won’t get rid of my American accent either.
So I took my American passport and put myself in line for foreigners.
I was thinking about that moment this week when future Mexican President Enrique Pena Nieto visited the White House to meet with President Obama.
On the agenda were all those themes that one expects when the heads of these two countries meet: immigration, drugs and trade.
Pena Nieto was also very interested in talking about the growth of the Mexican economy, which is one reason why Mexicans are just as likely to stay in Mexico instead of emigrating to the United States.
He wants to ally with the United States and Canada and create a North American trade bloc following the example of the European Union.
And Pena Nieto vowed to continue Mexico’s war against the drug cartels, even though he did not give any details about it.
Mexico’s relationship with the United States is complicated and full of resentment.
Most Americans probably never waste a single thought that the United States invaded Mexico in 1848, forcing the country’s gun leadership to leave more than half of its territory to them.
But for Mexicans who think in centuries rather than in minutes, memories of this event are not to be overlooked.
So once a U.S. government official makes even the slightest criticism of Mexico, you hear complaints — in the Mexican press and among the country’s elites — about how the Americans are pushing the sovereignty of their neighboring country.
And the children of Montezuma set out on the path of war.
And yet Mexico’s biggest challenge in truth lies in the relationship with the more than 35 million Mexican Americans living in the United States.
Want to talk about resentment?
There is more than enough.
Mexico has winners and losers, people for whom the country offers opportunities, and others for whom it does not.
The only reason so many people of Mexican descent live in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio is because at one point in our family tree a person—perhaps a parent or grandparent—was not offered a chance in Mexico and emigrated to the north.
And in most cases, this person corresponded to a profile - dark-skinned, uneducated, from a poor village, etc.
We are the descendants of these people, and our faithfulness is to them.
Not Mexico.
And although we may have now lived the American dream, attended good schools, and received good jobs, we must never lose sight of the fact that it is the American dream we live - not the Mexican one.
Our identity may sometimes be blurred, but as far as our loyalty is concerned, this is not the case.
This clearly applies to the United States.
In addition, we are aware that many members of the Mexican leadership class dislike us.
This is based on reciprocity.
They see us as a memorial of a humiliating defeat and look down on us because we are not Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough, our bands to Mexico will never be strong enough.
In their opinion, our existence is a symbol of failure.
If our families hadn’t failed in Mexico, they wouldn’t have left.
And then we wouldn’t be trapped behind the silk curtain now – with a pleasant life in the United States, but somehow lost.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and legally immigrated to the United States as a child, reminds me that there is tension between Mexicans and Mexican Americans because Mexicans have a clearer idea of who they are – and Mexican Americans disgust them.
While she is a U.S. citizen, she sees herself as part of two countries.
But many Mexican Americans I know feel like they don’t belong to either country.
We love the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but also Bruce Springsteen.
One enjoys the best of both worlds, but is not rooted in any of them.
In Mexico, we are seen as Americans.
And in the United States, we are seen as Mexicans.
As I should learn during my trip, there is something that makes this relationship even more complicated: Some Mexican leaders and parts of the educational bourgeoisie want to re-establish their connections to the diaspora.
They want to deploy Mexican Americans as provisional "ambassadors" to Mexico who represent their interests in the United States.
We are to tell our American colleagues how great a visit to this country is and to put pressure on the political leadership to intensify their ties to Mexico.
Oh, well.
That won't happen.
Too many hurt feelings.
And given the unjust income distribution, unbridled corruption and drug violence, many of us aren’t so sure if it’s really a great country.
I'm afraid you'll have to go through it alone, Amigos.
That's fair.
If at least some Mexicans are not ready to forgive the United States for dealing with Mexico one and a half centuries ago, they must also accept that some Mexican Americans have a resentment for how their family members were treated not so long ago.
Hmmmm. (chuckles)
Maybe we're more "Mexican" than I thought.
Old battles, new Middle East
The ceasefire between Israel and Hamas could prove to be an unexpected pillar of peace
Can there ever be lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
The latest bloody events seem to suffocate such hope in the germ.
Amidst the usual blame, countless buildings have been laid in rubble, more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis killed - and for the first time rockets have been deployed from Gaza near the Israeli metropolis of Tel Aviv and the holy city of Jerusalem.
But even though Israelis and Palestinians seem trapped in their historical conflict, the Middle East around them is changing.
The Arab Spring has created a new, uncertain situation, and whether they like it or not - Palestinians and Israelis have become part of this mess.
Perhaps this will only lead to more bloodshed.
But there are reasons to believe that the deadly stalemate could finally come to an end.
A war that is neither lost nor won
At first glance optimism seems far from appropriate in view of the current situation.
Even if the ceasefire agreed on November 21 continues, the fighting this week has strengthened the hard-boiled on both sides.
The leaders of Hamas, the Islamist movement that has controlled the Gaza Strip since 2007, claim to have pushed back the Israelis, despite the fact that its group itself suffered great losses.
Although several Hamas leaders are killed and the 1.7 million inhabitants of the Gaza Strip are trapped in one of the most desolate and densely populated corners of the planet, Israel has so far failed to destroy Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is winning in the West Bank, which is controlled by the rival, moderate Palestinian group Fatah.
And Hamas leaders may conclude that they have time on their side.
Just as Islamists have gained influence in the Arab world, Hamas has been able to draw powerful and rich friends on its side.
Turkey, a resurgent, regional power once considered Israel’s closest Muslim ally, has seized the party for Hamas – just like Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic Gulf states.
Jubilant Hamas supporters believe that Israel is forming an Islamist crescent — from Lebanon in the north, where militant Hezbollah has power, to Syria, where rebels in an increasingly Islamist direction may face the overthrow of Bashar Assad, to Jordan, where Hamas allies threaten the king.
And in particular, the rise of the Muslim Brotherhood under President Muhammad Morsi in Egypt - the by far the strongest and most important Arab country - on the southern flank of Israel has changed the balance of the region sustainably.
Hosni Mubarak, the secularist despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his fall in 2011, had little time left for Hamas.
In contrast, the fraternity with Hamas is merged and its leaders are more dependent on popular views.
In future diplomatic negotiations, Hamas could prove to be an actor that cannot even be pushed out by Israel and the United States.
The Israeli hardliners, on the other hand, draw an opposite conclusion.
From a military point of view, Hamas is no longer a danger.
The Israeli missile defense system, "Iron Dome", has proven itself and many of the Hamas missiles have been destroyed.
At least for a while, Israel will be able to sleep quieter.
In diplomatic terms, the United States remains steadfast in its position, and many European countries have blamed Hamas for the latest escalations of violence.
Israel has done well in recent years, especially under Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu, who has largely ignored the peace process.
Although rockets from the Gaza Strip have killed about 30 Israelis since 2004, the country has remained relatively free of suicide bombers - not least thanks to the blockade facilities that run into the West Bank and thus into the main part of a possible Palestinian state, protecting the Jewish settlements, which have been declared unlawful, but are still expanding.
Netanyahu's Likud party has joined forces with an even more fighting group in the run-up to the January 22 elections under Avigdor Lieberman.
Why do these deceitful Palestinians, too, deceive themselves and leave them a state of their own?
If they really had control over the West Bank, wouldn’t they fire rockets just like their fellow Gazans?
No, it is better to keep them in check behind the wall and punish them if they dare to raise their heads.
Maybe the hardliners will be able to win, but the Arab spring could make a blow to them.
Even if the Islamists who are now in power in Egypt and other countries have little left for Israel, they will initially focus on the difficulties in their own country.
Israel’s defense state is larger than that of its four Arab neighbors combined.
A war with the local superpower will hardly help the new Arab governments to restore their economy.
The fact that pragmatic President Morsi and Barack Obama have come together to reach a ceasefire could be a promising sign — and perhaps symbolize the beginning of a new era.
Israelis should also think more long-term.
While the rest of the Arab world is taking timid steps towards democratization, Palestinians continue to be deprived of their right to self-determination — a powder keg that will undoubtedly one day explode in the Israeli-occupied areas, just as a bus exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
Oppression is already undermining democracy in the Jewish state, and with the growth of the Arab population, this situation will only worsen.
Bloody missions to push back Hamas in the Gaza Strip will increasingly demand their diplomatic tribute over the years.
Both sides need a push from the outside
The correct answer is the one represented by the more sensible representatives of both sides, the majority of the rest of the world, and by this newspaper: two states in which Israel designs territories for security purposes.
The hope - small for the near future - is that the ceasefire will give outsiders more influence to enforce this solution.
Egypt must now, together with Turkey and Qatar, stop arms supplies to the Gaza Strip and is better positioned than ever before to convince Hamas of the idea of a Jewish state based on the 1967 borders, complemented by territorial exchange and a common Jerusalem.
External Arab nations should also push Hamas and Fatah to reach an agreement.
This would do more for the creation of a Palestinian state than the forthcoming request for UN observer status.
Obama must also contribute his part to pushing Israel to negotiate.
During his first term, he failed to present his own peace plan.
Far away in the White House, it seems he is also unwilling to participate.
But this is a regrettable, short-sighted perspective.
The United States has an essential interest in a stable Middle East.
This includes a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
Australia’s Unified Cigarette Packaging Laws Come Into Force
Health warnings and diseased body parts on neutral green packs that are the same for all tobacco brands
The world’s first unified cigarette and tobacco packaging laws came into force in Australia, replacing brand logos and colors with neutral, olive-green lids, which are also printed with drastic images showing sick body parts and infants and children who are sick from cigarette smoke.
Apart from the different health warnings and images, the only difference between the packages in the brand names, which are printed in identical, small lettering, is from Saturday.
Australia thus introduces the world’s most stringent regulations for tobacco packaging.
The Australian federal government wants to stop young people from smoking by eliminating the glamorous image of tobacco use.
The government is based on studies that have shown that people who haven’t started smoking at age 26 are 99% more likely to stop smoking afterwards.
"You can see that even young children understand the message that tobacco companies are trying to promote their brand image," said Federal Health Minister Tanya Plibersek, citing studies that have shown, for example, that children associate the crown of a logo with the idea of a princess.
Although Australia has one of the lowest smoking rates in the world and the changes will have only a slight impact on the profits of multinational corporations, other countries are already considering similar steps.
The tobacco lobby fought hard against the laws.
It was said that the laws would favour black market trade, leading to cheaper and more accessible cigarettes.
“The laws will lead to serious, unintended consequences,” says Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco Australia.
Chinese and Indonesian counterfeiters will offer much larger quantities of these products on the roads of Australia.
Others, on the other hand, say that the laws have boosted their business.
Sandra Ha of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family business, notes that demand for cigarette cases and silicone caps to cover the intolerable packaging has risen enormously since the British American Tobacco, Britain's Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco companies two months ago contested the Australian Supreme Court's law.
Zico has sold up to 6,000 units to wholesale stores and is awaiting new inventories.
This is a good deal for us.
According to experts, the hook in the popularity of social media lies with exactly the population group to which the plan is directed.
A number of Australian laws have banned tobacco companies from TV advertising, banned them from acting as sports sponsors, and forced most traders to stop cigarettes in stores. Now tobacco advertising has switched to the internet.
The Australian government has banned internet advertising by local companies and sites, but has no influence on international sites.
“Those who market tobacco and have only a small area left to promote their products don’t get around the internet,” says Becky Freeman, a health researcher at the University of Sydney.
On social media like YouTube, Twitter, and Facebook, Freeman has noticed an increase in reviews of brands written by “pretty ordinary people.”
You have to ask yourself the question: is this just a private person who likes Marlboro cigarettes so much that they even record a video for it - or does a marketing agency have to do with it?
British American Tobacco Australia says the industry is focusing on dealing with the new laws instead of marketing.
It has even gone so far as to pay Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new regulations - those countries complain to the World Trade Organization about unfair trade restrictions, although none of the countries operates major trade with Australia.
A WTO decision is expected in mid-2013.
According to Plibersek, the government has been in talks with other countries that are considering similar packaging laws.
Canada was the first country to prescribe photographic warnings in 2001.
These have now been expanded to more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
Tougher laws are being considered in the UK, New Zealand, South Africa and India.
Many Australian smokers are defiant.
The pictures do not affect me.
I just ignore them.
"You just take a tilt and put the box away," says Victor El Hage when buying a cigarette box with a photo of a mouth tumor printed on it.
Honestly, there's only one reason I'd quit, and that's my little girl.
James Yu, operator of the “King of the Pack” tobacco trade in downtown Sydney, says the unified packaging has made it difficult to refill its shelves.
“It used to take me an hour to sort a delivery, now I need four,” Yu says.
"The government should have completely banned cigarettes - then we would have said okay, that's it, we're closing down," he added.
In a constantly electrified world, it’s nice to be bored
This Thanksgiving I unexpectedly spent five hours at the airport when our plane crashed due to mechanical problems and we had to wait for another plane.
So I had enough time to think about boredom.
I don't want to lie.
Waiting for a flight half a day at the airport is pretty annoying – even when books, magazines and iPhones (and of course tax-free shopping) are available.
But more and more academics and child development experts point to boredom as something positive.
When it comes to them, it’s okay for us – and our children – to be bored occasionally.
Thus, the brain is forced to lose itself in interesting thought processes, which may promote creativity.
And because most of us these days are almost constantly staring at one screen or the other, the benefits of boredom no longer benefit us.
So should we welcome boredom with open arms?
Oh, yeah.
No, no, no.
I'll come back to that.
Like many people, I have always assumed that boredom is a relatively current phenomenon that has developed with increasing leisure time.
But Peter Toohey, professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary in Canada and author of Boredom: A Lively History (Yale University Press, 2011) does not see this as such.
“In fact, boredom has a very long history,” he says.
The house walls of Pompeii adorn a Latin graffiti about boredom dating back to the first century.
And then there is the question of how we actually define boredom.
According to John D. Eastwood, an associate professor of psychology at the University of York in Ontario, Canada, the problem is that boredom has been defined and discussed in many ways.
After long reading of research literature and presenting the idea to a focus group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues concluded that boredom is the experience of "wanting to do a satisfactory job but not being able to do it."
Boredom differs from apathy in that the person is not busy, but wants to be.
With apathy, on the other hand, there is no urge to do anything.
The key experience of boredom, he says, is a “disruption of the attention process, coupled with a bad mood and the feeling that time is only slowly passing by.”
Boredom can sound almost like depression.
But Professor Eastwood believes, although these two conditions may be related, bored people see the problem in their environment or the world, while depressed people see the problem in themselves.
Sometimes we think we’re bored, even if we’re just having trouble concentrating.
In their study "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention" - for example: "The Inactive Mind: The Definition of Boredom from the Aspect of Attention", which appeared in September in the journal "Perspectives on Psychological Science", Professor Eastwood and his colleagues point to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a volume in front of a person's magazine article.
Some groups listened to a loud television program from the neighboring room that had nothing to do with the content; others listened to it at low volume, so it was barely noticeable, while the third group did not hear these noises at all.
The people who heard the hardly audible television reported feeling more boredom than the other two groups - they had trouble concentrating, could find no reason for them and attributed their difficulties to boredom.
Trying to focus on a difficult or strenuous task can lead to boredom, says Mark J. Fenske, associate professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the authors of the study.
On the other hand, if you are engaged in a monotonous activity - "like the search for faulty products on a factory conveyor belt, music can distract and help not to feel bored".
In fact, he says, we now know that rumblings and scribbles, often interpreted as a sign of boredom, can even combat it by keeping people physically more attentive.
“Studies have shown that children who are allowed to hook around learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to sit still,” says Professor Fenske.
We all get bored at some point - my delayed flight, a thundering loudspeaker, a particularly tiring film.
But some people get bored easier than others.
To measure these differences, researchers in the 1980s developed a "boredom susceptibility scale".
On the scale there are statements such as “many things I have to do repeat themselves and are monotonous” and “I have so many interests that I don’t have enough time for everything.”
Using such scales, researchers have found that boys get bored more often than girls, according to Stephen Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida — particularly as it comes to the need for more and a greater variety of external stimuli.
But in general, teenagers are a fairly relaxed pile.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of human and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted nearly 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day with a pager.
He found that 32% of adolescents were bored in school and doing homework, while 23% reported being bored when they were not in school.
Only 3% of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson says today, 21 years later, he does not know whether the percentages of boredom have increased or decreased.
However, he is confident that "youth will be felt as particularly boring," mainly because children and teenagers do not have a great influence on their daily routine.
So back to my original question: Is boredom healthy?
Sometimes not, because in extreme cases, it causes people to take extreme physical risks and turn to gambling or drugs to relieve them - studies have shown.
On the other hand, many philosophers and authors investigate the relationship between boredom and creativity. This opinion is from Professor Vodanovich, who has been exploring the subject for more than two decades.
“With boredom, the brain wants to tell you to do something else,” said Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at the University of New York.
But the brain doesn’t always know what to do best.
If you’re bored and you use that energy to play and cook guitar, you’ll be happy.
However, television can cause feelings of happiness in the short term, but they disappear again in the long term.
So, if you give your bored child an iPad, it can distract him from boredom, but he has not learned to entertain or control himself, says Professor Fenske.
And he adds: “Self-control is transferred from one situation to another.”
The child not only learns to talk, but also gains more self-control in other areas.
I don't think we should celebrate boredom.
Nor should we look too critically at them.
Instead, our goal should be to feel at ease even away from the constant activity and technology challenge.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
"It sounds like we need to be bored more often, but boredom is the tormenting, incessant desire to do something meaningful," he says.
He believes that people in truth are just looking for a way to turn off and relax.
“In an environment where we are constantly over-stimulated, it’s hard to get busy once the noise is silent.”
In Colorado, there is no clear guideline for the new marijuana law
19-year-old community college student and soccer player Anthony Orozco stands trial in southeastern Colorado for a crime that will soon be legal in that state: the possession of a few fewer marijuana pieces and a pipe that he smoked them with.
According to Orozco, he and some friends were driving in Lamar near the Kansas border on a September day when they were stopped.
