The police authorities no longer pursue adults over the age of 21 for possession to a small extent, which will be allowed by law as soon as the new laws come into force in the coming weeks.
But prosecutors in Colorado’s more conservative districts have announced to continue prosecuting existing marijuana offenses and are still quoting people in court.
At the same time, several cities, from the suburbs of Denver to the Western Mountains, are voting to prevent new, state-licensed marijuana businesses from opening in their communities.
“This situation is evolving so fast that I don’t know what’s going to happen next,” said Daniel J. Oates, chief of police in Aurora, east of Denver.
Regulators in the state of Washington are also scratching their heads.
They are waiting for guidance on setting up a licensing system for the production, production, distribution and sale of the drug - with a deadline in mind until December 1, 2013.
In Washington, it is believed that Colorado is in any case ahead of most states when it comes to the regulation of marijuana, where the drug was only legalized for medical purposes and then for self-consumption.
