On November 21, Chief Oates sent an email to his staff in Aurora stating that the prosecutor would no longer prosecute minor marijuana offences against people over the age of 21, and that the police “from now on” would not seek criminal charges for these offences.
Chief Oates added that police would continue to enforce urban regulations to regulate medical marijuana growers and drug traffickers would continue to be persecuted.
In Weld County in northern Colorado, District Attorney Ken Buck has a more stringent view.
After the vote, he said his authority would continue to pursue cases of marijuana possession, mainly to get consumers to withdraw.
Currently, 119 people are held accountable for possession of about 50 grams or less of marijuana in court, although many have also been charged with other offences.
"Our authority has a duty to prosecute violations that at the time were crimes," Buck said in a statement.
The reactions are divided even in places like rural Mesa County, where voters rejected the marijuana initiative.
Police in Grand Junction, the largest city in the county, no longer indicate adults for possession of smaller quantities.
District Attorney Pete Hautzinger supported this decision, but also decided not to drop all pending possession proceedings.
“I don’t think I’m wasting my time enforcing the law until it changes,” he says.
Although 55% of voters in Colorado supported the measure, it was clear from the outset that it would not be easy to reconcile personal marijuana use with the complexities of government and the legal system.
And the contradictory reactions throughout the state fostered a profound division among local officials in view of the great green experiment.
District attorneys are a “cultural barrier,” says Sean McAllister, a Denver-based lawyer who represents defendants in court for marijuana offenses and acts on the ground as a spokesman for the national marijuana reform organization.
“They have spent such a large part of their lives prosecuting people for legalizing them that they still cannot accept legalization,” he believes.
As the first states to treat smaller amounts of marijuana such as alcohol, Colorado and Washington are treated as national standard cases for the legalization of drugs.
While advocates and state officials are preparing for an era of legal sales, they are also nervously waiting for instructions from the federal government, which wants to continue to treat the sale and cultivation of marijuana at the federal level as a criminal offence.
Advocates of the legalization movement hope that the Ministry of Justice will give in.
Despite several eye-catching arrests of medical marijuana consumers and sellers, the federal government has largely allowed the sale of medical marijuana in Colorado, Washington and 16 other states.
Kevin A. Sabet, former drug policy adviser to the Obama administration, believes that while criminal officers are unlikely to enter doors to seize smaller amounts of drugs, they are likely to avoid tolerating legal, state-regulated marijuana business under the new legislation.
Several cities in Colorado are not waiting for the federal authorities to act.
Even before Election Day, some local municipalities approved moratories for new marijuana businesses, although they could only open in about a year.
Last week, Montrose, a city in the west, decided on a six-month ban, which is likely to be passed next week.
“We don’t want to get into a position where we license someone and then face a big problem at the federal level,” said Bob Nicholson, a member of the City Council.
Our community has voted against this law change.
We are based on what the community has chosen, not what the state has chosen.
Many questions remain open.
Petronella Wyatt: I was bullied from Oxford because I'm Tory
It’s not just today’s university students who are being attacked for their views.
It has always been my biggest dream to get a place at Oxford University.
Both my father and my older brother had attended that university, which I once considered to be the greatest temple of knowledge in the world, for a modern Greek symposium that promoted the great pillars of civilization - free thinking and tolerance.
But within two weeks of my entry into Worscester College in the late 1980s – where I had planned to study history – I had packed my bags again and brought about the first scandal of my life.
My father broke down in tears.
My friends were confused.
The Evening Standard said I left because I had a problem with classmates having sex in the neighboring room.
The author A. N. Wilson said that I had left the university because I was forced to drink from damaged cups.
The truth was less amusing.
I ran away.
Yes, I ran, because I suffered from systematic bullying and threats.
Not because of my unusual name or because I came from a private school.
I had only been harassed for one reason – a reason that seemed so narrow-minded and cruel in this alleged cradle of enlightenment: my late father Woodrow Wyatt had been an important adviser to Margaret Thatcher and I had been a supporter of the Conservative Party.
Why am I mentioning this right now?
Well, according to recent reports, a new generation of moderate-rights students is suffering from similar persecution.
The organized and rising hatred of Tory students in Oxford has now developed such dimensions that a group of them demanded the same protection of equality last week that benefits gay, disabled and ethnic minorities.
Conservative members of Corpus Christi College's Junior Common Room (JCR) say they are "often actively isolated, personally attacked and declared undesirable" because of their political views.
They are demanding a seat on their college’s equality committee to ensure that their opinions can be freely expressed.
Their situation was exacerbated by a recently aired documentary about political students on BBC Two, “Wonderland: Young, Bright and on the Right,” which portrayed Tories as eccentrics and neo-Nazis.
Among other things, it showed graduate Joe Cooke, former president of the Oxford University Conservative Student Association, who rode in a Rolls-Royce and rode in silver suit and silver-clad walking stick.
At other universities, conservative students say they are considered “sinn goats for introducing higher tuition fees.”
The 20-year-old Luke Black, vice president of the conservative student association of the University of Nottingham, said in a Sunday newspaper: "There is a growing tendency of left-wing universities.
“People think we’re like the Bullingdon Club without ever getting to know each other.”
Samuel Roberts, 21 and a history student at Corpus Christi, who initiated the request for greater protection, believes such a climate is “unpleasant.” 19-year-old Stephanie Cherill, appointed president of the Oxford Conservative Student Association, says she has seen a growing rejection of moderate-rights students among JCR members.
“This poses a threat to intellectual discourse and members’ well-being,” she says.
In my first weeks in Oxford, I belonged to such a minority.
As an incredibly shy 18-year-old I arrived in September 1986.
The hatred of the Conservative Party had reached its peak.
Last year, the university voted not to give Margaret Thatcher - a former student - an honorary title due to cuts in higher education.
The atmosphere would have even frightened Stalinists.
In the first days of the first semester week, when new students get to know each other and the tutors, I got a taste of the future events.
I had the experience that the tutors not only tolerated the mockery of Tory students, but even participated with pleasure.
Political issues such as the miners’ strike, privatization and the government’s rejection of sanctions against South Africa’s apartheid regime found their way into the wood-panelled rooms of the tutorial.
At my first of these events, I was supposed to translate French texts from the 18th century into English.
"Miss Wyatt," said tutor Harry Pitt (now deceased), "please translate the first paragraph."
I stumbled on it.
Pitt was a little man with a face like cake dough, and quite ugly.
“Do Thatcher fans refuse to learn French, or are they just stupid?” he asked me.
The other students were giggling.
In my eyes there were tears.
"I suggest that they take a few French lessons in your free time - so if you're not too busy with your social activities," Pitt murmured.
I went back to my room with my head hanging.
That evening, I was sitting alone in college at dinner, when someone slightly tapped me on my shoulder.
It was a second-year English student named James, who introduced himself as a member of the Conservative Student Association.
“I know who you are,” he said kindly.
Unfortunately, it is as it is.
Anyone suspected of being Tory will be harassed.
It's bad enough for me, but they know your father, Margaret Thatcher, is close, so it's gonna be worse for you.
Most Tory first semesters pretend to be supporters of the Labour Party.
At a local pub, I later tried to make up my mind.
I insisted that I did not agree on all points with Mrs. Thatcher.
This trick should prove to be unsuccessful.
A freshman in philosophy, politics and business who ironically attended the conservative Eton College told me, "You are the daughter of a fascist pig."
You're dirty.
Other students shared his opinion.
I was perverted and dirty.
"How did Tories have sex?" one asked me.
They're beating each other, aren't they?
I felt like gays had to feel before the more liberal legislation of the United States.
Would I ever manage to live a normal life at Oxford University?
Would I be able to meet like-minded people after dark?
Should I turn to the Labour Party and suppress my natural inclinations?
The three years before me stretched before my spiritual eye to a purgatory of denial and isolation.
The only tutor to openly reveal himself as Tory was Norman Stone, a professor of contemporary history who was based in my college.
He was hated not only for being a conservative, but also for advising Thatcher on foreign policy and writing speeches for them.
He was rarely there.
He hated the place, found it provincial and small-scale, and rejected it for its Marxist-deterministic perspective of history.
In 1997 he took up a professorship at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
“You’re not going to be happy here,” he told me.
I started commuting between Oxford and my parents’ house and found refuge with more open-minded friends and family members in the city.
I told my father that I hated Oxford, and why I did it.
He seemed unbelieving.
During his time in the 1940s, all political views were accepted.
“But it’s the best place in the world,” he said aloud.
They would never do such a thing, not in my city of dreaming tower peaks.
Even my communist friends always showed up flawless manners.
His wet eyes blurred.
Give it a chance.
I'm sure they'll just tease you.
It would break my heart if you left.
Exhausted by my frequent trips to London, my emotional resistance weakened.
One of my male friends, also a Tory supporter, had given in to the pressure and renounced his beliefs.
During a tutorial the following week, in which another history tutor had seriously claimed that I was “an enemy of the people,” I decided to do the same.
Although I was secretly ashamed, I admitted that my parents had subjected me to "brainwashing" and called them "old idiots."
The relief only lasted a short time.
It was my father who hit the last nail in the coffin of my Oxford career.
At that time, he wrote two columns a week in the Murdoch Press.
My door was locked.
I hid in my room, and after five minutes my hookers gave up.
When they left, I packed a suitcase and took the first train to London.
I never returned.
You can call me a weeping cock.
But no 18-year-old should ever suffer from such intimidation and malice in an educational institution.
And even more tragic is that it was Oxford – a university that not only produced 14 Tory prime ministers, but still hides behind an undeserved reputation for equality and freedom of thought.
