The most difficult profession in the world: the human working animals by Kawah Ijen
For four euros, the carriers of the Indonesian volcano put their lives and health at risk when they carry 70 kilos of sulphur over the steep, rocky paths.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others literally work in hell.
This is the case with Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn their lives by taking sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, it must climb down to the ground of its crater every day, where the sulfur-containing gas emanating from the earth solidifies in contact with the air.
After breaking out large sulfur stones that can weigh up to 70 kilograms in total, he transports them in two bamboo baskets on his shoulders over the steep paths of stone.
While it is only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to a height of 2386 meters, the exhausted carriers need more than 40 minutes to climb at the tortoise speed, keeping their balance and putting their steps carefully so that they do not slip and fall.
They know that every step can cost their lives, as happened to a French tourist who crashed years ago on the slopes of Kawah Ijen.
The mine workers at Kawah Ijen earn 5 eurocents for every kilo of sulphur they mine.
Arriving at the top, they make their way between the tourists, who photograph them like circus monkeys, and run with the weary baskets three kilometers to the scale, which a mining company has set up a little further down at an altitude of 1850 meters.
The company is PT Candi Ngrimbi, who has been exploiting the volcano since 1960 and (never better) its workers, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 Eurocent) for each kilo of sulphur.
This is then sold for 10,000 rupees (83 eurocent) each to the petrochemical industry, because this mineral is widespread in everyday life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to bleach sugar.
"Since we normally carry 70 kg, we get about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each route," explains Anto, who usually does three routes a day.
For each route, it takes three hours, after which he is completely done, but at the end of the day he has 138,000 rupees (11,5 euros) together.
What looks like a miserable wage for such a seemingly inhuman effort is three times what he would earn from field work.
"The daily wage of the miners here, where the coffee harvest pays 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) per day and the average monthly income is two million rupees (167 euros) is very high," explains the carrier, who previously worked as a bricklayer on the tourist island of Bali.
There he earned 75,000 rupees a day, and the work wasn’t that hard, but Anto and his family returned to Banyuwangi, a nearby village, for a reason that is as important in Indonesia as sulfur: “I married a girl from Bali where they are Hindu, and I brought them to Java to convert them.”
Anto has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs frequently and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases.
The 27-year-old Anto has been putting his life at risk for three years on the Kawah Ijen, whose sulfur has already left his first traces, even though he covers his face with a mask and special glasses.
Anto has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs frequently and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases from the volcano.
This is the price he has to pay for achieving his dream.
“I’m going to work here for two more years because I want to open a store or learn Spanish or French,” he promises in more than just acceptable English.
This sympathetic and intelligent young man, but punished by life, could work as a tourist guide, waiter or receptionist at a hotel, but instead he does the work of a tragedy.
He shares a dirty wooden hut with other wearers and gets up every morning at two o’clock, because the sulfur also flows out at night, where its characteristic yellow color shines bluish in the dark.
Challenging the shadows, he climbs into the crater in the light of a small headlamp on his helmet, which he bought for his own money.
Approximately 400 carriers load the baskets with sulfur on their shoulders on the crater floor.
Despite its large profits, the mining company has not mechanized sulphur mining to save costs, and does not supply any equipment to carriers who work on their own account and are paid by weight.
You will also not receive any part of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) per camera that the guards of this nature park together with the admission fee of 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) demand from the tourists who come to photograph the volcano and the human dragon.
"This work is for animals and not for humans," Madrusin, a stubborn 42-year-old carrier who has been working at Kawah Ijen for three decades since leaving school, protests.
