“I’m not going to retire, I’m going to die here because the volcano has been my whole life,” says Unainik, opening his mouth wide where some teeth are missing.
Of his five children, the eldest at age 30 also works as a sulfur carrier.
Time passes, but the impoverishment continues generation after generation in one of the toughest professions in the world: the one of those who work as a human load esel on the Kawah Ijen.
Singapore needs babies to save the economy
The Singaporeans blame the lack of children on their careers, the stress and costs of real estate and child-rearing.
“Singapore’s population needs to grow.”
I am a patriotic husband, you are my patriotic wife: let us fulfill our civil duty and create life!
It seems unbelievable that the verses are part of an advertisement for mint candy, but nonetheless - or precisely because of - they became a viral video on YouTube earlier this year in Singapore.
The sentences are part of a rapper song, the local proverbs such as "pushing a "bao" (laid) into the furnace to make fun of the low birth rate in Singapore.
The advertising company BBH, which shot the video, maintains the hope that the advertisement will reach out to the problem in a funny way.
Her creative director Douglas Hamilton says he wanted to use the power of music to get people to fulfill their “national duty.”
This is something just for the internet, so we had to make it funny and funny.
This is the biggest problem in this country.
When it comes to reproduction, we are the worst in the world, so we realized that this is a topic that we had to take care of.
We knew that the government had tried a lot, such as marketing perfume with pheromones or organizing speed dating nights (fast flirts).
Possibly many of these ideas were creative, but they did not necessarily lead to success.
So we thought, “Why don’t we do something as creative as possible to tackle this problem, such as composing a rap?”
1.2 Children
Those who do not take this issue lightly are the government of Singapore.
Every year, it spends $1,300 on policy measures to encourage citizens to have more children.
A government package for married couples and parents grants up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave, and distributes tax benefits.
But everything has so far had little success.
Singapore is a rich, high-tech city state in Southeast Asia, also known for its rulers’ conservatism and its strict social controls.
According to its national population authority, the birth rate is currently 1.2 children per woman.
The last time this rate was above 2 — also known as the replacement rate — was in 1976.
So why don't Singaporeans have more kids?
Tan Wei Ming, director of marriage and family policy at the National Population Authority, says this is due to “better education” and “greater career opportunities.”
“This has enabled people to have significantly more choices in terms of life goals and priorities than to marry and form a family,” she explains.
These changes in social conditions have contributed to the higher number of singles and delays in marriage and births, the result of which is a reduction in the birth rate in Singapore.
Meanwhile, an immigration policy aimed at a drastic increase in immigration to counter the population reduction led to resentment among the local population.
In Singapore, there are websites where the hardly concealed xenophobia blooms against many new immigrants, especially the Chinese, who are criticized for keeping wages low and not integrating.
The rise in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why the ruling party in Singapore achieved its worst election result since independence last year.
Since the elections, an attempt has been made to correct the problem with higher contributions and levies for foreign workers.
Unexpected consequences
While the falling birth rate has the known impact on a nation’s economic growth, tax revenues, health care costs, and immigration policy, the Singapore example also shows unexpected consequences.
The government is trying to make sure that not so many small apartments are built.
It also has an impact on the housing market.
The City Development Authority has begun to control the number of small apartments known as "shoe boxes" that are allowed to be built in certain areas of the city.
These apartments have a living area of 46 square meters and show a great sales success.
However, there is concern that they can promote the lifestyle of the lonely, and that they will deter construction companies from building large housing for families.
But Lim Yew Soon, general manager of real estate company EL Developers, says his “shoe boxes” can be sold much faster than larger housing units.
They are so popular, and the units are sold out by days and even weeks faster than the larger units.
This makes them much better for our cash flow.
However, he admits that the new standards provide clearer guidance to developers who had previously been put in the way of obstacles if they wanted to build too many small housing units within a project.
Too much stress
Singapore is a city state.
Even if these new rules could pave the way for a rise in the national birth rate, talks with Singaporeans working in the financial district show that they will have little effect.
"People are very stressed, the apartments and the education are expensive, which is why it is postponed by many," says a young manager.
The children can get others.
“For me, it’s important to have my own money and time,” says another man, about twenty years old.
Men and women cite their careers, the stress and the cost of ownership and education as reasons why they cannot have children.
That's why Singaporeans have the last word when it comes to having children - there's so much the government can do.
The offline Private offline is online private
Privacy policy
According to the dictionary, this is the property private or "that area of private life where you have a right to protection from any kind of interference".
What is private for someone under the age of 16?
How is this definition applied to your daily life and social networks?
Does he understand the dangers he faces when he makes known situations on the Internet that he would not share in real life?
El Periódico interviewed five young people between the ages of 10 and 15, who often travel online.
In four of the cases, they linked the term to "something very own" on a personal level and "to the password and the user" when they applied it to social networks.
“I wouldn’t reveal my deepest secrets in a post,” says 10-year-old Jorge as he tries to explain the meaning of “private” on websites like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has had accounts for two years.
