The boy is aware that it is wrong to post obscene photos, of naked people, of crimes, or to write offensive or violent comments.
Jorge assured to know 35 friends he has on FB and nine followers on Twitter.
Most of them are relatives.
This includes the mother who has the password to one of the accounts.
I signed up on Twitter to express myself and write interesting tweets.
“I don’t know if anyone will answer me, I’ll just upload them,” he adds.
“The social networks are entertaining, I can talk quickly to relatives in the distance or with friends,” he said.
Asked he would never accept an invitation from an unknown.
Even if someone offered him a stranger, he would ignore it.
The case of the 14-year-old José is different.
The teenager has user accounts in Hotmail, Facebook, My Space, and Ask. In Ask, he admits to not knowing 20 of the people he has added to his friend list.
“It doesn’t scare me because we have something in common, like music,” he says.
No one made hints about the boy or asked him for his address or phone number.
"If someone pushes me or asks for them from me, I just remove them from my user account," he admits.
José contacted Ask after reading a recommendation on Twitter.
The boy is not unfamiliar with experiences that are now known as cyberbullying.
A friend's acquaintance was blackmailed on a social network.
They threatened him and demanded money.
“He never knew who it was,” he assured.
According to José, the victim did not close the user account.
“He just made it private.”
After that, he explains a series of steps to configure a user account securely.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would upload photos of acquaintances in uncomfortable or embarrassing situations.
Yeah, I'd do that if he's unsympathetic to me or I want to wipe one out of him.
“But I know this is cyberbullying,” he explains.
Key questions
Marielos Porras, English teacher with a university degree in education and learning, believes that in order to guide children and young people, it is necessary to understand that it is the purpose of social networks to inform.
“The Internet was created as a medium for searching for information, but with the appearance of these sites, the rules of the game have changed,” she says.
Porras explains that the academic Marc Prensky, holder of a master's degree in pedagogy at Yale University and author of the work "Digital Natives and Immigrants" formed these terms to explain the phenomenon.
They are the digital natives, the children and young people who grew up with this technology.
“We are the digital immigrants who are supposed to teach them when we are still learning ourselves,” he says.
He explains that this is a complex issue “because we require them to have a defined criterion for what can be disseminated, published or said, and this at an age where maturity is insufficient for it.”
“They should also be selective when it is most important to them to be popular, to have thousands of friends without thinking about the consequences,” he adds.
According to the expert, the most effective way to teach children and adolescents what privacy is to ask them questions that make them think.
“Tell them not to do it doesn’t work,” he says.
Porras then mentions some options: There are things you wouldn’t tell a stranger. Why do you do it on the internet?
Or: Would you like to have a photo of you posted like the one you posted from a friend?
Do you know what others post about you?
Have you asked the other people for permission beforehand when you tagged photos of celebrations?
And one more question: Do everyone have to know what you do at any moment?
Another point is to give them to understand that they need to act online as they do offline.
It's the same rules.
“Someone outside the Internet acts with respect, morality and other principles, and the same must apply to social networks,” he explains.
Surveillance
Estuardo Guardia, university professor, elementary school teacher and educator, commented that it is indispensable that parents carefully read the guidelines of social networks.
If they understand all the sections, they have a solid foundation to talk to their children about the importance of opening a user account on the internet.
"For example, the age, or what you can share or publish," he explains.
According to Guardia, the children must be reminded of the lesson "You must not talk to strangers".
Conclusion of the UNAZUR Summit without publication of the Lima Declaration
The 6th Summit of the Presidents of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) ended today in Peru without publication of the Lima Declaration, which was previously announced and was theoretically to be signed by the seven present leaders.
Efe repeatedly tried to gain access to the signed document at the Sixth Ordinary Meeting of the Heads of State and Government of the Unasur. Sources in the State and Presidential Office initially informed that they would hand it over after the exam, but later stated that it would be published on the Peruvian government's website at some time.
When asked about the text, they indicated that the content was presented by the President of Peru, Ollanta Humala, in brief statements to the press.
Journalists' access to information about the summit was limited at any time.
During the day, only the image of the presidential meeting without sound with the message "private session, limited audio" was transmitted in the press room.
The few information circulated among the journalists was received by the press spokesmen of some of the UNAZUR governments present at the meeting, but not by the Peruvian press spokesman.
The only document circulated during the day was the list of participating presidents, causing discomfort among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who demanded more information.
Afterwards, the Peruvian presidential office sent the media an e-mail with the "declaration of the conclusion" of the summit, which was the Humala declaration and not the official document concluding the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third Summit of South America-Arab States (ASPA), and even on this occasion, despite a press call, the so-called Lima Declaration, which was previously announced, was not published either.
On the official website of the ASPA you can be convinced that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities stressed the existence of information systems for journalists, but they severely restricted access to information.
The summit also concluded with the joint commitment of Chile and Peru to adopt a judgment of the Court of Justice of The Hague, which resolves a border conflict between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Pi<0xC3><0xB1>era, met during the regional meeting, confirming that they would accept the decision of the ICC, which begins Monday in The Hague, in the process of initiating Lima against Santiago, to hear the pleas of both sides.
“We will follow and execute the ruling on the differences we are currently bringing to this international court,” Humala said.
“Chile was, is and continues to be a country that adheres to international law, seeks peaceful solutions to disputes, concludes agreements and submits to international courts,” added Pi<0xC3><0xB1>era, greeting Humala with a handshake before the flags of both countries.
The confirmation by both presidents that they would submit to the ICC came after Colombia, following a decision on the maritime borders with Nicaragua, considered it a serious mistake, filed a lawsuit against the Bogotá Agreement, in which it agreed to submit to the judgments of this International Court of Justice.
The summit was attended by the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rousseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, which has been excluded from unasur since 2011 after the removal of its president Fernando Lugo, did not attend the meeting.
Host President Ollanta Humala opened the talks in the morning and ended the summit in Lima shortly after noon.
The head of state read the final document, stating that 16 decisions have been made and the lines of action for 31 projects between the South American countries have been set for a total investment of $17 billion.
He said the UNAZUR countries “will take significant steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, for which we are extending the decisions on residence rights.”
He said that measures would be pushed forward to “improve cooperation in the fight against insecurity in cities and against organized, transnational crime, as well as measures to improve access to medicines and the Internet at low prices in all areas of South America and to act jointly and efficiently in the event of natural disasters.”
With the crisis in Europe, "economic consolidation (in Latin America) must not take on triumphant traits, but should serve to expand our production output and show our people a better future," Humala added.
"We have decided to give priority to a series of 31 emblematic projects designed to improve the spatial connections in South America and especially in rural and border areas ... and thus unite our countries and develop new forms of economics," the Peruvian president said in a read statement.
Among these projects would be five Peruvian, which would lie on the transverse axes of its territory from the coast to Brazil, and two of which would provide a better connection with Ecuador, although he gave no further details.
The final document also referred to the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the election process in this country will serve to re-establish it in the Union of South American Nations, from which it is currently excluded."
The need for Latin America to continue to remain an integrated region for prosperity and peace and with good neighbourly relations was another aspect that was emphasized at the summit.
In this regard, the President of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, before beginning his participation in the regional meeting, said that he expected a meeting with his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico to treat the maritime conflict with respect after a ruling of the ICC questioned by Bogotá.
"I may be meeting with President Daniel Ortega tomorrow," Santos said.
"We will review all of these pathways - they are not exclusive, and the agreement with Nicaragua also necessitates talks with Nicaragua," he said.
"I hope to tell President Ortega that we will deal with this matter as civilly and respectfully as possible," Santos said.
Santos and Ortega would meet in Mexico on Saturday, where they intend to be present at the inauguration of the country’s new president, Enrique Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto.
As part of the summit, the defence ministers of the bloc also met in advance to adopt the 2013 action plan, which aims to strengthen dialogue and consensus on the defence of the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are members of UNASUR, although the latter country is currently excluded.
Peru has the presidency at the time of the regional bloc.
