Cause of dying due to AIDS today is a late detection
Fabrizio was 21 years old when he was confirmed to be HIV-positive.
“It was like a bomb hit,” he says of the moment he was diagnosed, which the doctor tried to “weaken down without noticeable success.”
He hid it from his family.
He decided to take care of his illness alone and began to find out about it; and this with such dedication that he was just celebrating his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the oldest patients in the HIV unit of the Hospital Civil de Guadalajara (HCG), to which he came after several fights in 1994.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, which was hard to imagine in the early 1990s when there were many doubts, few treatment options and more stigmata.
At the time, even the director of an IMSS clinic avoided saying goodbye "because it led to a dead end."
At that time, AIDS was synonymous with death.
Today, it is possible to survive this syndrome with quality of life.
However, many people still come to the clinic who are unaware of their disease and in whom the virus has already done damage and exhausted their immune system, and are victims of opportunistic infections.
31 years after the appearance of AIDS in the world, i.e. after the first reported cases, "the great success today means that the survival of a patient who starts treatment on time and the survival of the general population are exactly the same," said Jaime Andrade Villanueva, head of the HCG HIV unit.
Infectious Diseases and HIV/AIDS specialist Andrade Villanueva commented that since 2008, scientists have concluded that although AIDS is not a death sentence, years of survival and quality of life depend on the degree of impairment of the immune system of people at the start of treatment, and that those who are not dependent on CD have a greater chance of CD of 200 years and up to 30 years.
Simply put, the above statements mean that whoever is diagnosed HIV-positive at the age of 25, in this sense "can easily turn 75 years old as long as he is under control," this expert explained.
In order to properly classify this progress, it must be remembered that the average life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years.
Although mortality has decreased significantly in recent years (in Mexico, the number of people dying of AIDS has decreased from 6,678 cases in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011, according to the UNAIDS annual report), it is still true that 60 percent of patients recorded in the national database have died since the appearance of AIDS.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and by the month of May of this year there are already 187 deaths; however, it is assured that there has been universal access to antiretroviral drugs since 2005.
- So why are people still dying?
- In my opinion, the problem is not access to treatment.
This is my opinion, and so it is in our hospital.
At least in the last 12 years, we have had no problems with the supply of medicines. The problem is that people come to a far advanced state because they do not know their condition of infection, i.e. in very late stages of the disease.
He makes a striking statement: "Nine out of ten patients come to us if they already have a concomitant infection. In order to affect global mortality, earlier diagnoses are required, which is why massive detection tests must be offered to all those who need to do so."
The experts and officials of the Consejo Estatal de Prevención del AIDS en Jalisco (Coesida) (State Committee on AIDS Prevention in Jalisco) and also the patients like Fabrizio, who had his test carried out at a private laboratory, agree on this proposal for the sole reason that it had made a friend of him who had already been in the AIDS-like stage (and even had been a complicated) despite his young age.
Everything is different when you know you have AIDS.
Some think they’re going to die and don’t want to hear anything.
"If I have to die, I'd rather burst three times," they say in my case.
The change was to improve, I eat well, exercise and take the medication.
Today his parents only know that he had cancer.
I live a normal life, just like everyone else.
“I work, I do a lot, I have an active but responsible sex life, I pay attention to my health and that of the other person,” says Fabrizio, who agreed to share his intimate details with MILENIO JALISCO in order to animate with his testimony those who are afraid today as part of the worldwide AIDS Day.
They should take the test if they belong to the risk group. The sooner they know if they are HIV-positive, the better, and if they already know the diagnosis, they should learn how to live responsibly like all people.
His message is a summary of the fight against AIDS in 2012.
Condoms behind the counter
There are big holes between the health programs and the ordinary citizen, explains Ricardo Salazar, a journalist from Guadalajara who has taken on the cause of HIV.
And the most important thing is prevention.
In the designated places "the distribution of condoms was actually increased; before they were given individually, now they give us packages with a hundred pieces, which is already good, but there are still people who do not have access to a condom," he said.
Among those at risk for new infections are adolescents.
"Why do you need this?" is a common mockery question from social workers, mentoring staff in schools, pharmacy workers and the healthcare system who do not want to expose themselves, the correspondent assured.
He proposed to reorient this inefficient distribution; the condoms should not only be behind the counter, but in output devices in public toilets of facilities that are frequently visited by young people.
Promise is not to be promoted.
They should not be paid for the beer and motel, as Governor Emilio González answered the question of whether condoms would be distributed under his administration.
“Sexuality doesn’t look like this; it’s best to bring condoms closer to those who are already engaging in sexual activity,” he said.
Key data of Jalisco
There are 13,435 cumulative cases (12,158 AIDS and 1,317 HIV).
The state ranks 4th in new and cumulative AIDS cases, and 13th in HIV.
92% of cases of infection occur through intercourse, 6% via blood and 2% perinatal.
It is estimated that 50,000 people live with HIV because there are 4 or 5 people in every registered case who do not know it.
After the U.S. Court of Appeal has upheld a ruling that fails to recognize the restructuring of the liabilities of the Vitro Group achieved through a trade bankruptcy in Mexico, an unfortunate precedent is created for any national company with branches in the neighboring country that has payment problems.
So it could be said that the procedures for the survival of companies that allow Mexican laws are not valid in the country of stars and stripes, contrary to international agreements.
In practice, the June 15 recognition of the judgment by Judge Harlin Hale in Bancarrotas court for the northern district of Texas has resulted in Mexican companies being helplessly exposed to the seizure of their property beyond the Bravo River.
However, the decision opens doors to the largest glass manufacturer in Mexico to appeal to the Supreme Court of the United States for three inconsistencies.
While the judge of the case points out that creditors must be subject to U.S. bankruptcy law, the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeal, based in New Orleans, initially states that the main proceeding is the commercial bankruptcy dealt with in Mexico.
The first point would mean that international cooperation in insolvency proceedings of companies with cross-border profiles is not known.
In fact, for this purpose, the United Nations Model Law for the Uniformation of International Trade Law was created, using the American Law Institute as a mediator.
Second, the judgment determines that without the votes of the companies, after acknowledging the liabilities in the bankruptcy estate that Vitro’s branches had with their parent company, the necessary majority for the restructuring of the liabilities would not have been achieved.
However, this possibility is recognized by Mexican laws.
In fact, Vitro is not the first case in which this scheme has been approved.
There are half a dozen examples, including Agremex and Comercial Mexicana, whose liabilities to group companies have been confirmed by the Instituto Federal de Concurso Mercantiles (Federal Institute for Trade Bankruptcies).
It is also correct that, after deducting the votes of the branches, the creditors of Vitro, the creditors who sued Vitro in the United States courts, i.e. the vulture funds such as Aurelios Capital, Aurelios Convergencia, Elliot Internacional and Liverpool Limited, would not have reached a majority.
The vote would have been 45 percent against 37 percent.
This is not taken into account by the Court of Appeal.
On the other hand, Vitro is to blame for its difficult situation from 2008 onwards as part of the great economic crisis in the United States that hit the country.
For this reason, the González Sada family appeals to the same Court of Appeal to ensure that the vote takes place in the plenary, i.e. of all the judges, because only three of them voted.
If it is not granted, Cerciorare’s appeal is filed, which requires review of the proceedings by a higher authority, in this case by the Supreme Court of the United States.
The serious thing about this case is that the court has set aside a document sent by the Government of Mexico under the figure amicus curiae (friend of the court) describing the proceedings carried out by Vitro under the Trade Bankruptcy Act, and pointing out that it had strictly adhered to the agreements signed by both countries in order to comply with Chapter 15 of the United States Bankruptcy Act.
It is also noted that the country has adhered to the principles of the United Nations Commission on International Trade, i.e. the established rules for cases of cross-border insolvency that guarantee the equality of debtors and creditors.
Two-banded caramboles: a blow for Vitro and for the country.
