Héctor "Hetin" Reyes: "Basketball was my life"
Basketball world hiker, Héctor "Hetin" Reyes, has been linked to basketball for more than 60 years and has travelled the world.
Few in Puerto Rico have such a large intellectual collection of the country's basketball history as Héctor "Hetin" Reyes.
Before being tied to the wheelchair by a stroke in 2008, Rexes was part of this sport for 6 years, whether as a player of lower classes, player of the first national league, representative and leader of the BSN with the Vaqueros de Bayamón or president of the basketball association.
"I have put on many hats in basketball throughout my life, even several at the same time when I was president of the BSN, chief executive of the national team and president of the association in the 1990s," Reyes recalled during a visit by Primera Hora to his home in Bayamón, where he lives with Isabel, his loyal wife for more than 50 years.
"Basketball was my life."
Reyes does not exaggerate with this statement.
The walls of his house are almost all decorated with photos and memories of his long career and testify to them.
Bayamón in the heart
The most emotional memories are those reminiscent of his time with the Vaqueros from the mid-50s as a player until 1982, when he celebrated his 15th anniversary as a co-CEO or managing director of the club.
“These were my best years I’ve enjoyed the most because I’ve been part of eight Vaqueros championships since 1967, whether as a CEO, co-CEO or coach.
It was many fulfilling years, including the five consecutive championships from 1971 to 1975.
And then I said goodbye to a championship in 1981, the year of Jerome Mincy’s debut at BSN.
From then on, "Cuco" Ortiz took over, who was a very good manager," says Reyes.
I remember Gene Bartow, who worked here as a coach and was employed at the University of Alabama (Birmingham), said to me: "I have a very strong and 2m player.
Do you want him?"
And that was the beginning of Mincy, one of the best players Puerto Rico has ever had.
Bartow then recommended the free throw specialist Raymond Gausse, who became a citizen and was one of our best throwers.
I remember how he said that if Mincy had enabled a championship for Bayamon, Gausse would provide for another.
The championship of the Vaqueros with Gausse was granted to him, but already from a distance, because he was already in the top position of the association in 1988.
At that time, he preferred to enjoy his executions and that of Mincy in the national team.
I remember the first time we won the U.S. at the pre-Olympic tournament in Mexico.
“Then came the 1990 World Cup, where we took fourth place in what should have been bronze if it hadn’t been for this Canadian referee who had us repeat the last round for the second time,” Reyes said.
Was this group from the 1990 World Cup the best national team you've ever seen?
She is one of the best, as well as the one who won the 2004 Olympics against the Dream Team.
But my favorite is the team at the 1991 Pan American Games in Cuba, where we won gold and offered a fight to the US team, like when they won bronze against us at the World Cup.
